<i>Earn five points for every trivia question
you answer correctly.</i>

18
00:01:02,188 --> 00:01:06,442
<i>As a bonus, if you catch a glimpse
of the Golden Snitch gliding,</i>

19
00:01:06,526 --> 00:01:09,571
<i>or even hiding in a scene
where it shouldn't be,</i>

20
00:01:09,654 --> 00:01:12,323
<i>give yourself an additional 25 points.</i>

21
00:01:12,407 --> 00:01:17,537
<i>Be certain to stay after the film for
the house cup ceremony to see how you've done.</i>

22
00:01:17,620 --> 00:01:20,832
<i>So give it your best go.
You might even win the house cup.</i>

23
00:01:22,375 --> 00:01:25,587
<i>Now start yourjourney
and let the magic begin.</i>

24
00:01:51,362 --> 00:01:52,822
{\an8}Hi, I'm Chris Columbus.

25
00:01:52,905 --> 00:01:56,909
{\an8}I'm here to walk you through
some of the more exciting scenes

26
00:01:56,993 --> 00:01:59,370
{\an8}from <i>Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone,</i>

27
00:01:59,454 --> 00:02:03,666
{\an8}or, if you're in England,
<i>Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone.</i>

28
00:02:04,459 --> 00:02:07,337
{\an8}A lot of these scenes bring back
some amazing memories for me,

29
00:02:07,420 --> 00:02:11,215
{\an8}and I hope they bring back some good memories
for you from when you first saw the film.

30
00:02:46,793 --> 00:02:49,170
[CAT MEOWS]

31
00:02:49,712 --> 00:02:54,717
I should've known that you would
be here, Professor McGonagall.

32
00:03:05,895 --> 00:03:09,065
{\an8}Good evening, Professor Dumbledore.

33
00:03:11,567 --> 00:03:14,570
Are the rumors true, Albus?

34
00:03:14,862 --> 00:03:20,076
{\an8}I'm afraid so, professor.
The good and the bad.

35
00:03:20,284 --> 00:03:23,538
{\an8}- And the boy?
- Hagrid is bringing him.

36
00:03:23,788 --> 00:03:27,709
{\an8}Is it wise to trust Hagrid
with something so important?

37
00:03:28,209 --> 00:03:32,714
Professor, I would trust Hagrid
with my life.

38
00:03:34,757 --> 00:03:36,509
{\an8}[ENGINE ROARS]

39
00:03:51,941 --> 00:03:56,112
{\an8}Professor Dumbledore, sir.
Professor McGonagall.

40
00:03:56,320 --> 00:03:59,574
{\an8}- No problems, I trust, Hagrid?
- No, sir.

41
00:03:59,741 --> 00:04:05,163
{\an8}We're gonna first start in a scene
where Harry is delivered

42
00:04:05,246 --> 00:04:10,001
{\an8}onto the Dursleys' front porch by Dumbledore,
and this is an interesting scene,

43
00:04:10,084 --> 00:04:13,296
{\an8}because we actually had
to film the scene with a real baby

44
00:04:13,379 --> 00:04:15,798
{\an8}and we found some triplets

45
00:04:15,882 --> 00:04:20,052
{\an8}who were able to work in 20-minute increments.

46
00:04:20,136 --> 00:04:26,058
{\an8}And I just remember the one distinct thing
I remember about shooting this scene,

47
00:04:26,142 --> 00:04:33,149
{\an8}is that the baby was such
a very jumpy, nervous sleeper,

48
00:04:33,232 --> 00:04:38,196
{\an8}that we had to walk around
on our tiptoes and whisper,

49
00:04:38,279 --> 00:04:41,365
{\an8}so you had a film crew of 150 people

50
00:04:41,449 --> 00:04:43,576
{\an8}whispering throughout this entire scene.

51
00:04:43,659 --> 00:04:46,746
{\an8}It's probably the most quiet scene
I've ever filmed.

52
00:04:47,330 --> 00:04:52,627
{\an8}And then there was the problem
of actually applying Harry's scar,

53
00:04:52,710 --> 00:04:55,963
{\an8}which was fresh at this point in the story.

54
00:04:56,047 --> 00:04:58,049
{\an8}It just happened.

55
00:04:58,132 --> 00:05:01,302
{\an8}Applying Harry's scar
onto the forehead of the baby

56
00:05:01,385 --> 00:05:05,723
{\an8}was something that was impossible to do.
We just couldn't apply prosthetics to the baby.

57
00:05:05,807 --> 00:05:09,602
{\an8}So the scar was actually digitally created.

58
00:05:09,685 --> 00:05:12,730
{\an8}And I remember doing that close-up of the baby,

59
00:05:12,814 --> 00:05:14,899
we needed to just be extraordinarily quiet.

60
00:05:14,982 --> 00:05:18,444
And it took us several takes because
the baby was always waking up and crying.

61
00:05:18,528 --> 00:05:22,156
It was actually one of the most calm nights
I've ever had on a film shoot,

62
00:05:22,240 --> 00:05:24,784
because everyone was pleasant and whispering.

63
00:05:24,867 --> 00:05:27,829
And we came up with this idea
when we were shooting the film

64
00:05:27,912 --> 00:05:32,124
{\an8}that it would be great to use the scar
as a transition between baby Harry

65
00:05:32,208 --> 00:05:36,003
{\an8}and when we first introduce
Daniel Radcliffe into the film.

66
00:05:39,131 --> 00:05:42,093
WOMAN:
Up. Get up!

67
00:05:44,720 --> 00:05:46,222
Now!

68
00:05:59,944 --> 00:06:03,322
DUDLEY: Wake up, cousin!
We're going to the zoo!

69
00:06:14,500 --> 00:06:19,755
{\an8}PETUNIA: Here comes the birthday boy.
VERNON: Happy birthday, son.

70
00:06:21,591 --> 00:06:24,760
{\an8}Cook breakfast.
And try not to burn anything.

71
00:06:25,011 --> 00:06:29,974
- Yes, Aunt Petunia.
- I want everything to be perfect...

72
00:06:30,182 --> 00:06:33,102
...for my Dudley's special day!

73
00:06:33,269 --> 00:06:38,274
- Hurry up! Bring my coffee, boy.
- Yes, Uncle Vernon.

74
00:06:39,525 --> 00:06:42,612
PETUNIA:
Aren't they wonderful, darling?

75
00:06:44,780 --> 00:06:48,534
- How many are there?
- 36. Counted them myself.

76
00:06:48,618 --> 00:06:51,704
36?! But last year I had 37!

77
00:06:51,954 --> 00:06:55,791
- But some are bigger than last year's.
- I don't care!

78
00:06:55,875 --> 00:06:58,544
This is what we're going to do.

79
00:06:58,753 --> 00:07:03,049
We're going to buy you two
new presents. How's that, pumpkin?

80
00:07:05,092 --> 00:07:10,431
{\an8}PETUNIA: It should be a lovely day
at the zoo. I'm looking forward to it.

81
00:07:14,018 --> 00:07:15,811
{\an8}I'm warning you now, boy.

82
00:07:16,062 --> 00:07:19,565
{\an8}Any funny business, any at all...

83
00:07:19,774 --> 00:07:22,818
{\an8}...and you won't have
any meals for a week.

84
00:07:23,569 --> 00:07:25,321
{\an8}Get in.

85
00:07:32,495 --> 00:07:34,914
{\an8}DUDLEY:
Make it move.

86
00:07:37,583 --> 00:07:39,293
Move!

87
00:07:39,543 --> 00:07:42,004
- Move!
- He's asleep!

88
00:07:42,171 --> 00:07:44,757
{\an8}He's boring.

89
00:07:47,176 --> 00:07:52,598
{\an8}Sorry about him. He doesn't understand
what it's like, lying there...

90
00:07:53,140 --> 00:07:56,936
{\an8}...watching people press
their ugly faces in on you.

91
00:07:59,689 --> 00:08:01,941
Can you hear me?

92
00:08:04,860 --> 00:08:08,864
It's just, I've never talked
to a snake before.

93
00:08:09,365 --> 00:08:10,783
Do you...?

94
00:08:10,992 --> 00:08:15,121
Do you talk to people often?

95
00:08:16,205 --> 00:08:19,542
You're from Burma, aren't you?
Was it nice there?

96
00:08:19,709 --> 00:08:22,044
Do you miss your family?

97
00:08:24,880 --> 00:08:29,635
I see. That's me as well.
I never knew my parents either.

98
00:08:29,844 --> 00:08:34,849
Mummy, Dad, you won't believe
what this snake is doing!

99
00:08:57,913 --> 00:08:59,915
Thanks.

100
00:09:00,166 --> 00:09:01,584
Anytime.

101
00:09:04,920 --> 00:09:06,839
MAN:
Snake!

102
00:09:07,048 --> 00:09:11,135
[SCREAMING]

103
00:09:22,271 --> 00:09:25,649
Mum! Mummy! Help me!

104
00:09:25,900 --> 00:09:29,028
My darling boy!
How did you get in there?

105
00:09:29,528 --> 00:09:34,617
Who did this? How did you get
in there? Is there a snake?

106
00:09:39,455 --> 00:09:44,794
It's all right, sweetheart.
We'll get you out of these cold clothes.

107
00:09:46,545 --> 00:09:49,465
- What happened?
- I swear, I don't know!

108
00:09:49,673 --> 00:09:53,552
{\an8}The glass was there
and then it was gone, like magic.

109
00:09:57,973 --> 00:10:00,768
There's no such thing as magic.

110
00:10:13,072 --> 00:10:14,907
PETUNIA:
And smile!

111
00:10:15,616 --> 00:10:18,160
Oh! Vernon, just look at him.

112
00:10:18,244 --> 00:10:22,540
I can't believe it.
In just a week, he'll be off to Smeltings.

113
00:10:22,623 --> 00:10:26,669
<i>Caveat Smeltonia.</i> Proudest moment of my life.

114
00:10:26,752 --> 00:10:28,629
Will I have to wear that too?

115
00:10:30,506 --> 00:10:33,008
PETUNIA:
What? You go to Smeltings?

116
00:10:38,472 --> 00:10:39,890
Don't be so stupid.

117
00:10:39,974 --> 00:10:42,351
You're going to go to the state school
where you belong.

118
00:10:42,434 --> 00:10:45,980
This is what you're going to be wearing
when I finish dyeing it.

119
00:10:46,063 --> 00:10:48,149
But that's Dudley's old uniform.

120
00:10:48,232 --> 00:10:50,484
It'll fit me like bits of old elephant skin.

121
00:10:50,568 --> 00:10:52,153
It'll fit you well enough.

122
00:10:53,028 --> 00:10:55,739
Now go get the post. Go!

123
00:11:26,562 --> 00:11:29,231
VERNON:
Marge is ill. Ate a funny whelk.

124
00:11:29,440 --> 00:11:32,651
- Dad, look! Harry's got a letter!
- It's mine!

125
00:11:32,860 --> 00:11:35,613
Yours? Who'd be writing to you?

126
00:12:03,849 --> 00:12:06,268
[DRILL WHIRS]

127
00:12:06,894 --> 00:12:11,398
VERNON:
No more mail through this letterbox.

128
00:12:23,577 --> 00:12:26,413
PETUNIA:
Have a lovely day at the office, dear.

129
00:12:26,664 --> 00:12:28,165
[OWL HOOTS]

130
00:12:29,333 --> 00:12:32,002
Shoo! Go on.

131
00:13:02,032 --> 00:13:03,242
[OWLS SHRIEKING]

132
00:13:05,911 --> 00:13:07,538
[SCREAMS]

133
00:13:30,060 --> 00:13:32,438
Fine day, Sunday.

134
00:13:33,564 --> 00:13:38,235
In my opinion, best day of the week.
Why is that, Dudley?

135
00:13:38,444 --> 00:13:42,823
- Because there's no post on Sundays?
- Right you are, Harry!

136
00:13:43,073 --> 00:13:44,700
No post on Sunday.

137
00:13:45,242 --> 00:13:49,788
{\an8}Now we have the mail delivery scene here.
It was one of my favorite sequences in the film.

138
00:13:49,872 --> 00:13:52,916
{\an8}Why? Because we didn't resort
to digital effects.

139
00:13:53,000 --> 00:13:55,419
{\an8}We did when the owls arrive at Privet Drive.

140
00:13:55,502 --> 00:13:58,088
{\an8}We probably had four or five real owls,

141
00:13:58,172 --> 00:14:01,550
{\an8}and we supplemented the scene
by adding all these digital owls.

142
00:14:01,633 --> 00:14:05,429
{\an8}But every shot of the letters
that arrive through the fireplace

143
00:14:05,512 --> 00:14:06,680
{\an8}was done practically.

144
00:14:06,764 --> 00:14:10,100
{\an8}Now, today, even six, seven, eight years later,

145
00:14:10,225 --> 00:14:14,063
{\an8}we would have done this by creating CGI letters

146
00:14:14,146 --> 00:14:16,398
{\an8}and having the actors react to nothing.

147
00:14:16,482 --> 00:14:19,777
But I thought it would be great
if they had something tangible to react to.

148
00:14:19,860 --> 00:14:22,696
So we had our crack special effects supervisor,
John Richardson,

149
00:14:22,780 --> 00:14:25,991
come up with this method
of using an air shaft

150
00:14:26,075 --> 00:14:28,494
to blow hundreds of letters
through the fireplace.

151
00:14:28,577 --> 00:14:29,995
And it worked beautifully.

152
00:14:30,079 --> 00:14:34,541
{\an8}I, even, was fortunate enough to operate
one of the three cameras in this sequence,

153
00:14:34,625 --> 00:14:36,210
{\an8}so it's something I'm proud of.

154
00:14:36,293 --> 00:14:40,005
{\an8}Even though I direct films,
I would love to someday be a camera operator.

155
00:14:40,089 --> 00:14:41,256
{\an8}For me, it was fantastic.

156
00:14:41,340 --> 00:14:46,428
{\an8}Every shot you see here,
these are all filled with real, practical letters.

157
00:14:46,512 --> 00:14:50,057
{\an8}And I love this sequence
because you see, for the first time in the movie,

158
00:14:50,140 --> 00:14:53,685
{\an8}there's a sense of joy and happiness
in Harry Potter's face.

159
00:14:53,769 --> 00:14:58,732
{\an8}That's sort of the first time he feels
any sort of happiness in his life.

160
00:14:58,816 --> 00:15:01,693
{\an8}So, that's one of the other reasons
I really love this scene.

161
00:15:01,985 --> 00:15:04,655
Daddy's gone mad, hasn't he?

162
00:15:40,149 --> 00:15:41,859
Make a wish, Harry.

163
00:15:42,901 --> 00:15:49,450
{\an8}Hagrid's arrival, to basically free Harry
and tell Harry, for the first time, he's a wizard,

164
00:15:49,533 --> 00:15:51,577
this was quite a difficult scene to shoot,

165
00:15:51,660 --> 00:15:54,413
because we actually had to build
two of these huts.

166
00:15:54,496 --> 00:15:58,542
One of the huts was practical-sized
for all of the actors to work in,

167
00:15:58,625 --> 00:16:02,463
with the exception of Robbie Coltrane,
who was playing the giant Hagrid.

168
00:16:03,130 --> 00:16:06,633
{\an8}All of Robbie's material was shot
in a smaller hut,

169
00:16:06,717 --> 00:16:10,095
{\an8}so when Robbie himself, dressed as Hagrid,
walked through the door,

170
00:16:10,179 --> 00:16:12,890
{\an8}he appeared to be nine-feet tall.

171
00:16:13,849 --> 00:16:19,438
And we shot all of the reverses
with the Dursleys and Harry

172
00:16:19,521 --> 00:16:21,523
using a giant double

173
00:16:21,607 --> 00:16:24,067
that we created for a former rugby player,

174
00:16:24,151 --> 00:16:27,321
who has played Hagrid's double
in almost every film, I think.

175
00:16:27,404 --> 00:16:29,615
{\an8}And we created this wonderful
prosthetic mask.

176
00:16:29,698 --> 00:16:31,325
{\an8}So in long shots and wide shots,

177
00:16:31,408 --> 00:16:35,746
{\an8}if you're interested in seeing exactly how
we put this together,

178
00:16:35,829 --> 00:16:38,123
{\an8}you can actually see Harry walking,

179
00:16:38,207 --> 00:16:41,418
{\an8}sometimes walking through the streets of London,
with this double.

180
00:16:41,502 --> 00:16:43,462
{\an8}If you look close enough,
you can see the mask.

181
00:16:43,545 --> 00:16:45,589
{\an8}We only used it very sparingly.

182
00:16:45,672 --> 00:16:49,384
{\an8}When Hagrid walks through the door,
for instance,

183
00:16:49,468 --> 00:16:53,305
{\an8}we actually shot all of Robbie's things
on the smaller set.

184
00:16:53,388 --> 00:16:55,641
So this was an interesting moment
of directing for me,

185
00:16:55,724 --> 00:16:58,852
because I actually had to get
a performance out of Daniel Radcliffe,

186
00:16:58,936 --> 00:17:01,522
who should have been
emotionally moved at this point.

187
00:17:01,605 --> 00:17:06,235
Yet at the same time, he couldn't connect
with the other actor in the room, Robbie Coltrane.

188
00:17:06,318 --> 00:17:07,945
And that was a little difficult

189
00:17:08,028 --> 00:17:11,573
{\an8}because he was reacting
to a guy basically in a Hagrid mask.

190
00:17:11,657 --> 00:17:15,536
{\an8}So it was a complex puzzle piece
to put together.

191
00:17:15,619 --> 00:17:18,747
{\an8}In the end, I thought it all worked out well.
It's just a wonderful moment.

192
00:17:18,830 --> 00:17:22,292
{\an8}This is what happens when you work
with younger, inexperienced actors.

193
00:17:22,376 --> 00:17:25,003
{\an8}It's a wonderful moment
with Daniel Radcliffe there,

194
00:17:25,087 --> 00:17:28,006
{\an8}when he finds out
that he's a wizard for the first time.

195
00:17:28,090 --> 00:17:32,928
{\an8}It's just, again, this sort of joy
on his face. It's just fantastic.

196
00:17:33,011 --> 00:17:35,264
{\an8}It comes from the fact
that he had no acting lessons.

197
00:17:35,347 --> 00:17:38,767
{\an8}He was really experiencing
that feeling in a real way.

198
00:17:38,850 --> 00:17:43,897
Rubeus Hagrid, Keeper of Keys
and Grounds at Hogwarts.

199
00:17:43,981 --> 00:17:47,818
- Of course, you know about Hogwarts.
- Sorry, no.

200
00:17:48,360 --> 00:17:52,823
Didn't you ever wonder where
your mum and dad learned it all?

201
00:17:53,407 --> 00:17:55,033
Learned what?

202
00:17:55,117 --> 00:17:57,077
{\an8}You're a wizard, Harry.

203
00:17:58,996 --> 00:18:01,039
{\an8}- I'm a what?
- A wizard.

204
00:18:01,123 --> 00:18:04,251
{\an8}A good one, I'd wager,
once you're trained up.

205
00:18:04,334 --> 00:18:07,421
No, you've made a mistake.
I mean...

206
00:18:07,504 --> 00:18:10,465
...I can't be a wizard.

207
00:18:11,174 --> 00:18:15,929
I mean, I'm just Harry. Just Harry.

208
00:18:17,014 --> 00:18:21,101
Well, Just Harry, did you ever
make anything happen?

209
00:18:21,184 --> 00:18:24,688
Anything you couldn't explain,
when you were angry or scared?

210
00:18:27,774 --> 00:18:29,151
Hm.

211
00:18:42,247 --> 00:18:45,459
{\an8}HARRY: "Dear Mr. Potter,
We are pleased to accept you...

212
00:18:45,542 --> 00:18:48,962
...at Hogwarts School
of Witchcraft and Wizardry."

213
00:18:49,046 --> 00:18:54,134
He will not be going! We swore
we'd put a stop to all this rubbish.

214
00:18:54,217 --> 00:18:58,597
You knew? You knew all along
and you never told me?

215
00:18:58,680 --> 00:19:01,892
Of course we knew.
How could you not be?

216
00:19:01,975 --> 00:19:05,812
My perfect sister being who she was.

217
00:19:05,896 --> 00:19:11,860
My mother and father were so proud
the day she got her letter.

218
00:19:11,943 --> 00:19:16,198
"We have a witch in the family.
Isn't it wonderful?"

219
00:19:16,281 --> 00:19:19,993
I was the only one to see her
for what she was.

220
00:19:20,077 --> 00:19:22,162
A freak!

221
00:19:22,245 --> 00:19:25,374
Then she met that Potter,
and then she had you...

222
00:19:25,457 --> 00:19:31,213
...and I knew you would be the same.
Just as strange, just as abnormal.

223
00:19:31,296 --> 00:19:36,510
And then she got herself blown up,
and we got landed with you.

224
00:19:36,593 --> 00:19:40,681
Blown up? You told me
my parents died in a car crash.

225
00:19:40,764 --> 00:19:45,268
A car crash? A car crash killed
Lily and James Potter?

226
00:19:45,352 --> 00:19:49,398
PETUNIA: We had to say something.
- It's an outrage! A scandal!

227
00:19:49,481 --> 00:19:52,025
He'll not be going.

228
00:19:52,109 --> 00:19:55,612
A great Muggle like you
is going to stop him?

229
00:19:55,696 --> 00:19:56,697
Muggle?

230
00:19:56,780 --> 00:20:00,951
Non-magic folk. This boy's had
his name down since he were born.

231
00:20:01,118 --> 00:20:05,122
He's going to the finest school
of witchcraft and wizardry.

232
00:20:05,205 --> 00:20:11,169
He'll be under the finest headmaster
Hogwarts has seen, Albus Dumbledore.

233
00:20:11,336 --> 00:20:16,133
{\an8}I will not pay to have a crackpot
old fool teach him magic tricks.

234
00:20:16,299 --> 00:20:20,887
{\an8}Never insult Albus Dumbledore...

235
00:20:21,096 --> 00:20:23,140
...in front of me.

236
00:20:40,991 --> 00:20:46,288
I'd appreciate it if you didn't tell
anyone at Hogwarts about that.

237
00:20:46,371 --> 00:20:50,125
- I'm not allowed to do magic.
- Okay.

238
00:20:51,918 --> 00:20:54,921
We're a bit behind schedule.
Best be off.

239
00:21:01,094 --> 00:21:03,930
Unless you'd rather stay, of course.

240
00:21:18,695 --> 00:21:22,449
"First-year students will require
three sets of plain work robes,

241
00:21:22,532 --> 00:21:24,493
one wand..."

242
00:21:24,576 --> 00:21:26,620
Essential bit of equipment, Harry.

243
00:21:28,121 --> 00:21:30,290
"One pair of dragonhide gloves."

244
00:21:31,041 --> 00:21:32,834
Hagrid, do they mean from a real dragon?

245
00:21:32,918 --> 00:21:35,295
Well, they don't mean a penguin, do they?

246
00:21:37,297 --> 00:21:41,468
- Blimey, I'd love a dragon.
- You'd like a dragon?

247
00:21:41,551 --> 00:21:44,262
Vastly misunderstood beasts, Harry.

248
00:21:44,346 --> 00:21:46,640
Vastly misunderstood.

249
00:21:53,438 --> 00:21:56,775
{\an8}HARRY:
"All students must be equipped with...

250
00:21:56,858 --> 00:21:59,778
{\an8}...one standard size 2
pewter cauldron...

251
00:21:59,861 --> 00:22:04,825
{\an8}...and may bring, if they desire,
either an owl, a cat or a toad."

252
00:22:06,159 --> 00:22:07,536
{\an8}Can we find all this in London?

253
00:22:08,829 --> 00:22:10,163
{\an8}If you know where to go.

254
00:22:33,979 --> 00:22:37,023
Ah, Hagrid! The usual, I presume?

255
00:22:37,107 --> 00:22:40,527
No, thanks, Tom.
I'm on official Hogwarts business.

256
00:22:41,278 --> 00:22:44,489
Just helping Harry buy
his school supplies.

257
00:22:44,573 --> 00:22:47,534
Bless my soul. It's Harry Potter!

258
00:22:52,455 --> 00:22:55,417
Welcome back, Mr. Potter.
Welcome back.

259
00:22:56,084 --> 00:23:00,297
{\an8}Doris Crockford. I can't believe
I'm meeting you at last.

260
00:23:00,881 --> 00:23:06,177
{\an8}Harry Potter. Can't tell you
how pleased I am to meet you.

261
00:23:06,261 --> 00:23:08,847
{\an8}Hello, professor. I didn't see you.

262
00:23:08,972 --> 00:23:13,977
{\an8}Professor Quirrell will be your
Defense Against the Dark Arts teacher.

263
00:23:14,185 --> 00:23:16,563
Oh, nice to meet you.

264
00:23:16,855 --> 00:23:19,941
Fearfully fascinating subject.

265
00:23:20,025 --> 00:23:24,738
Not that you need it, eh, Potter?

266
00:23:25,697 --> 00:23:29,868
Yes, well, must be going now.
Lots to buy.

267
00:23:29,951 --> 00:23:31,828
HARRY:
Goodbye.

268
00:23:34,789 --> 00:23:38,126
- See, Harry? You're famous.
- But why am I famous?

269
00:23:38,376 --> 00:23:41,880
All those people,
how is it they know who I am?

270
00:23:42,047 --> 00:23:45,800
I'm not sure I'm the right person
to tell you that.

271
00:23:47,844 --> 00:23:51,848
{\an8}Here we have the Diagon Alley sequence,
which is one of my favorite sequences in the film.

272
00:23:51,932 --> 00:23:57,020
{\an8}It's fantastic because we actually created
this entire Diagon Alley set

273
00:23:57,103 --> 00:23:58,647
{\an8}on a soundstage in Leavesden.

274
00:23:58,730 --> 00:24:01,608
{\an8}Although, calling it a soundstage
is really not appropriate

275
00:24:01,691 --> 00:24:04,402
{\an8}since there were leaks,
we would always hear rain coming through,

276
00:24:04,486 --> 00:24:06,363
{\an8}we could always hear planes
flying overhead,

277
00:24:06,446 --> 00:24:09,908
{\an8}but it worked for us in terms
of the amount of space to build the set.

278
00:24:10,784 --> 00:24:14,079
{\an8}But this Diagon Alley set
was really a wonderful thing,

279
00:24:14,162 --> 00:24:18,208
{\an8}when we'd bring visitors to the set,
because it was part of our Harry Potter World,

280
00:24:18,291 --> 00:24:21,670
{\an8}you know, when we brought school kids to visit.

281
00:24:21,753 --> 00:24:24,255
{\an8}You could actually walk
down these cobblestone streets.

282
00:24:24,339 --> 00:24:28,802
{\an8}I really wanted Diagon Alley to have
this sort of warped, Dickensian feel,

283
00:24:28,885 --> 00:24:31,304
{\an8}and to feel as if it had existed
for hundreds of years.

284
00:24:31,388 --> 00:24:34,891
{\an8}So, this is really a major achievement

285
00:24:34,975 --> 00:24:39,354
{\an8}from our production designer, Stuart Craig,
who I think did a brilliant job

286
00:24:39,437 --> 00:24:43,024
{\an8}in his attention to detail in terms
of all these wizard shops

287
00:24:43,108 --> 00:24:44,275
{\an8}that exist on Diagon Alley.

288
00:24:44,359 --> 00:24:46,903
{\an8}It had to feel like a place
you had never been to before.

289
00:24:46,987 --> 00:24:50,198
{\an8}And we see it through Harry's eyes
which was my feeling about the whole film.

290
00:24:50,281 --> 00:24:52,575
It just had to happen
through Harry's point of view.

291
00:24:54,494 --> 00:24:56,705
BOY 1:
It's a world-class racing broom.

292
00:24:57,330 --> 00:25:01,459
In this particular moment, there's my son,
my son who is much older now,

293
00:25:01,543 --> 00:25:04,379
looking at the Nimbus 2000 in the window.

294
00:25:04,462 --> 00:25:07,799
{\an8}So, it's sort of like having
very expensive home movies for me to look at.

295
00:25:08,133 --> 00:25:12,679
But how am I to pay for all this?
I haven't any money.

296
00:25:12,887 --> 00:25:16,224
{\an8}There's your money.
Gringotts, the wizard bank.

297
00:25:16,474 --> 00:25:21,104
{\an8}Ain't no safer place, not one.
Except perhaps Hogwarts.

298
00:25:34,701 --> 00:25:38,747
{\an8}Hagrid, what exactly are these things?

299
00:25:38,830 --> 00:25:44,085
{\an8}They're goblins. Clever as they come,
but not the most friendly of beasts.

300
00:25:44,627 --> 00:25:46,337
{\an8}Best stay close.

301
00:25:47,213 --> 00:25:48,923
[HAGRID CLEARS THROAT]

302
00:25:50,258 --> 00:25:53,928
Mr. Harry Potter wishes
to make a withdrawal.

303
00:25:58,183 --> 00:26:01,352
And does Mr. Harry Potter
have his key?

304
00:26:02,270 --> 00:26:04,522
Wait a minute.
Got it here somewhere.

305
00:26:08,359 --> 00:26:11,196
Ha! There's the little devil.

306
00:26:11,446 --> 00:26:14,282
And there's something else as well.

307
00:26:15,533 --> 00:26:17,952
Professor Dumbledore gave me this.

308
00:26:22,957 --> 00:26:28,088
It's about you-know-what
in vault you-know-which.

309
00:26:29,297 --> 00:26:31,007
Very well.

310
00:26:36,471 --> 00:26:38,807
Vault 687.

311
00:26:41,226 --> 00:26:43,228
Lamp, please.

312
00:26:51,986 --> 00:26:53,321
Key, please.

313
00:27:16,886 --> 00:27:19,889
Did you think your parents
would leave you with nothing?

314
00:27:21,891 --> 00:27:25,687
{\an8}GOBLIN: Vault 713.
HARRY: What's in there, Hagrid?

315
00:27:25,770 --> 00:27:30,066
{\an8}HAGRID: Can't tell you.
Hogwarts business. Very secret.

316
00:27:30,150 --> 00:27:31,734
GOBLIN:
Stand back.

317
00:28:00,013 --> 00:28:02,807
Best not to mention this to anyone.

318
00:28:11,232 --> 00:28:15,153
{\an8}I still need a wand.

319
00:28:15,361 --> 00:28:18,907
You want Ollivanders.
There ain't no place better.

320
00:28:19,824 --> 00:28:24,579
Run along there and wait.
I got one more thing to do.

321
00:28:27,624 --> 00:28:32,170
{\an8}Here we have a scene that was
a real joy to shoot, Ollivanders Wand Shop.

322
00:28:32,253 --> 00:28:34,339
{\an8}And the great thing
about this particular scene,

323
00:28:34,422 --> 00:28:36,633
{\an8}it's the first time and the only time

324
00:28:36,716 --> 00:28:39,594
{\an8}that JK Rowling showed up
at the set to visit.

325
00:28:39,677 --> 00:28:42,764
{\an8}It was her only day there,
so I was a little nervous.

326
00:28:42,847 --> 00:28:45,350
{\an8}I walked her through Diagon Alley,
and she loved it.

327
00:28:45,433 --> 00:28:50,897
{\an8}She loved-- again, the attention to detail
that our production designer, Stuart Craig,

328
00:28:50,980 --> 00:28:52,523
{\an8}paid to every single shop.

329
00:28:52,607 --> 00:28:55,276
{\an8}Even if we weren't going inside
these particular shops,

330
00:28:55,360 --> 00:28:59,864
{\an8}there was an attention to detail to the shelves,
to the things that existed on the shelves.

331
00:28:59,948 --> 00:29:02,951
All of these boxes were individually made,

332
00:29:03,034 --> 00:29:06,955
hand-printed, stamped,
with the Ollivander Wand Shop logo.

333
00:29:07,038 --> 00:29:08,122
It was just unbelievable.

334
00:29:08,248 --> 00:29:12,710
...that your mother and father were
in here buying their first wands.

335
00:29:19,801 --> 00:29:22,095
Here we are.

336
00:29:30,645 --> 00:29:32,522
Give it a wave.

337
00:29:39,654 --> 00:29:41,239
Apparently not.

338
00:29:46,869 --> 00:29:50,999
{\an8}Another great thing about the Harry Potter films
is you get an opportunity to work with actors

339
00:29:51,082 --> 00:29:54,544
{\an8}who would never consider
coming in to do one or two days' work.

340
00:29:54,627 --> 00:29:56,087
{\an8}In this particular situation,

341
00:29:56,170 --> 00:29:57,797
{\an8}John Hurt, who was a fan of the books,

342
00:29:57,922 --> 00:30:00,466
{\an8}agreed to play Ollivander
for just a couple of days.

343
00:30:00,550 --> 00:30:02,051
{\an8}You don't see that in films a lot.

344
00:30:02,135 --> 00:30:05,555
{\an8}And so, it was wonderful
getting a chance to work

345
00:30:05,638 --> 00:30:07,515
{\an8}with one of my favorite British actors.

346
00:30:07,598 --> 00:30:10,977
{\an8}And also, again, in this Potter film,
this early Potter film,

347
00:30:11,060 --> 00:30:14,856
one of the things I love about it is
its sort of old-fashioned charm.

348
00:30:14,939 --> 00:30:17,525
A lot of these visual effects
in this particular sequence

349
00:30:17,608 --> 00:30:19,402
were, again, done practically.

350
00:30:19,485 --> 00:30:21,404
We didn't just resort to saying,

351
00:30:21,487 --> 00:30:25,992
"Okay, let's do them by digital effects.
Let's use CGI." We didn't do it here.

352
00:30:26,075 --> 00:30:27,702
{\an8}When Harry first gets the wand,

353
00:30:27,785 --> 00:30:32,707
{\an8}we wanted to create this magical moment
and feeling of power with the wand.

354
00:30:32,790 --> 00:30:35,835
{\an8}Well, that was created
by slowing the frame rate.

355
00:30:35,918 --> 00:30:37,712
{\an8}Film usually runs at 24 frames per second.

356
00:30:37,795 --> 00:30:40,673
{\an8}And we slowed the frame rate down
to 120 frames per second,

357
00:30:40,757 --> 00:30:44,385
{\an8}created a sense of smoke,
blew some wind through Harry's hair.

358
00:30:44,469 --> 00:30:46,262
{\an8}And thought, "If this works, we'll use it.

359
00:30:46,346 --> 00:30:48,723
{\an8}If not, we may need to enhance it
with digital effects."

360
00:30:48,806 --> 00:30:53,102
{\an8}It worked beautifully.
It created a sense of you being there.

361
00:30:53,186 --> 00:30:56,731
{\an8}And I love creating tangible effects in films,

362
00:30:56,814 --> 00:31:01,027
{\an8}because it really harkens back
to the old days of filmmaking.

363
00:31:01,110 --> 00:31:03,112
{\an8}And for me, this scene is...

364
00:31:03,196 --> 00:31:05,823
{\an8}We could have filled it with visual effects.

365
00:31:05,907 --> 00:31:08,493
{\an8}But it's all about the performances
of the two actors.

366
00:31:08,576 --> 00:31:10,661
Just one other.

367
00:31:10,745 --> 00:31:15,249
It is curious that you should
be destined for this wand...

368
00:31:15,333 --> 00:31:20,546
...when its brother gave you that scar.

369
00:31:22,882 --> 00:31:25,635
And who owned that wand?

370
00:31:26,928 --> 00:31:29,472
We do not speak his name.

371
00:31:29,931 --> 00:31:33,434
The wand chooses
the wizard, Mr. Potter.

372
00:31:33,518 --> 00:31:36,562
It's not always clear why.

373
00:31:36,896 --> 00:31:40,525
But I think it is clear...

374
00:31:40,608 --> 00:31:43,653
...that we can expect
great things from you.

375
00:31:44,862 --> 00:31:49,242
After all, He-Who-Must-Not-Be-Named...

376
00:31:49,325 --> 00:31:52,036
...did great things.

377
00:31:52,120 --> 00:31:53,621
Terrible...

378
00:31:54,580 --> 00:31:58,000
...yes, but great.

379
00:32:02,213 --> 00:32:03,381
{\an8}[KNOCKING]

380
00:32:03,464 --> 00:32:05,508
{\an8}HAGRID:
Harry! Harry!

381
00:32:05,883 --> 00:32:07,802
{\an8}Happy birthday.

382
00:32:09,762 --> 00:32:10,930
{\an8}HARRY:
Wow.

383
00:32:15,393 --> 00:32:18,896
You all right, Harry?
You seem very quiet.

384
00:32:19,272 --> 00:32:24,819
He killed my parents, didn't he?
The one who gave me this.

385
00:32:25,069 --> 00:32:28,781
You know, Hagrid. I know you do.

386
00:32:32,577 --> 00:32:36,164
First, and understand this
because it's very important:

387
00:32:37,331 --> 00:32:39,834
Not all wizards are good.

388
00:32:40,084 --> 00:32:42,753
Some of them go bad.
A few years ago...

389
00:32:42,879 --> 00:32:47,800
...there was a wizard who went as bad
as you can go. His name was V--

390
00:32:48,009 --> 00:32:51,804
- His name was V--
- Maybe if you wrote it down?

391
00:32:51,929 --> 00:32:53,681
No, I can't spell it.

392
00:32:53,931 --> 00:32:58,352
{\an8}- All right, Voldemort.
- V o I d e m o rt?

393
00:32:58,436 --> 00:33:00,813
{\an8}Shh.

394
00:33:02,148 --> 00:33:04,358
It was dark times, Harry.

395
00:33:06,694 --> 00:33:09,822
<i>Voldemort started
to gather some followers.</i>

396
00:33:10,072 --> 00:33:12,992
<i>Brought them over to the Dark Side.</i>

397
00:33:14,785 --> 00:33:17,872
{\an8}<i>Anyone that stood up to him
ended up dead.</i>

398
00:33:19,040 --> 00:33:21,375
{\an8}<i>Your parents fought against him.</i>

399
00:33:22,293 --> 00:33:25,755
{\an8}<i>But nobody lived once
he decided to kill them.</i>

400
00:33:30,468 --> 00:33:33,054
<i>Nobody, not one.</i>

401
00:33:33,137 --> 00:33:35,473
<i>Except you.</i>

402
00:33:37,642 --> 00:33:41,729
Me? Voldemort tried to kill me?

403
00:33:42,230 --> 00:33:46,400
Yes. That ain't no ordinary cut
on your forehead, Harry.

404
00:33:46,692 --> 00:33:52,406
A mark like that only comes from being
touched by a curse, an evil curse.

405
00:33:52,657 --> 00:33:56,244
What happened to V--?
To You-Know-Who?

406
00:33:57,411 --> 00:34:00,748
Well, some say he died.

407
00:34:00,998 --> 00:34:03,417
Codswallop, in my opinion.

408
00:34:03,626 --> 00:34:06,879
Nope, I reckon he's out there still...

409
00:34:07,088 --> 00:34:10,049
...too tired to carry on.

410
00:34:10,258 --> 00:34:15,137
But one thing's certain. Something
about you stumped him that night.

411
00:34:15,930 --> 00:34:20,184
That's why you're famous.
That's why everybody knows your name.

412
00:34:20,643 --> 00:34:23,187
{\an8}You're the boy who lived.

413
00:34:33,656 --> 00:34:35,825
{\an8}What are you looking at?

414
00:34:38,119 --> 00:34:40,121
{\an8}Blimey, is that the time?

415
00:34:40,204 --> 00:34:44,458
{\an8}I'm gonna have to leave you.
Dumbledore will be wanting his--

416
00:34:44,542 --> 00:34:49,589
{\an8}Well, he'll be wanting to see me.
Your train leaves in 10 minutes.

417
00:34:49,672 --> 00:34:53,593
Here's your ticket. Stick to your ticket,
that's very important.

418
00:34:57,930 --> 00:35:00,099
{\an8}"Platform 9 3/4"?

419
00:35:00,308 --> 00:35:05,229
{\an8}But, Hagrid, there must be a mistake.
This says platform 9 3/4.

420
00:35:05,313 --> 00:35:07,648
{\an8}There's no such thing, is there?

421
00:35:16,949 --> 00:35:19,285
{\an8}Here we have Platform 9 3/4.

422
00:35:19,368 --> 00:35:24,040
{\an8}Interesting scene, because we were
sort of forced into shooting this

423
00:35:24,123 --> 00:35:26,459
{\an8}at King's Cross Station on a Sunday,

424
00:35:26,542 --> 00:35:31,130
{\an8}obviously the least-busiest day
of the week for a train station.

425
00:35:31,213 --> 00:35:33,341
{\an8}So we all got there early on a Sunday morning,

426
00:35:33,424 --> 00:35:38,929
{\an8}and this particular sequence,
my assistant and my driver and my daughter--

427
00:35:39,013 --> 00:35:41,766
{\an8}That is my fellow, Harry,

428
00:35:41,849 --> 00:35:44,602
{\an8}who drove me throughout
the first three Potter films,

429
00:35:44,685 --> 00:35:47,271
{\an8}so we became very good friends
and I put him in my film,

430
00:35:47,355 --> 00:35:49,523
{\an8}in this Harry Potter film,

431
00:35:49,607 --> 00:35:53,861
{\an8}and he has since been--
He was put in the second Harry Potter film,

432
00:35:53,944 --> 00:35:57,531
{\an8}and then Tim Burton fell in love with Harry
and now Harry's in every Tim Burton movie.

433
00:35:57,615 --> 00:36:01,410
{\an8}So he's still driving,
but he gets a cameo in every British film.

434
00:36:01,494 --> 00:36:03,829
{\an8}This presented quite a problem for us

435
00:36:03,913 --> 00:36:09,168
{\an8}because, again,
my desire to do visual effects here practically,

436
00:36:09,251 --> 00:36:10,878
{\an8}obviously are not going to work

437
00:36:10,961 --> 00:36:13,881
{\an8}when someone has to pass through
an existing brick wall.

438
00:36:13,964 --> 00:36:19,345
{\an8}So we decided to actually do this
with digital effects.

439
00:36:19,428 --> 00:36:20,805
{\an8}And it works very well.

440
