00:51:46,104 --> 00:51:48,273
{\an8}of building something practically

664
00:51:48,356 --> 00:51:50,108
{\an8}and also creating a CG world.

665
00:51:50,191 --> 00:51:52,652
{\an8}When we first look up
and see all of the moving staircases,

666
00:51:52,736 --> 00:51:54,613
{\an8}obviously we could have never built that,

667
00:51:54,696 --> 00:51:57,282
{\an8}but we were able to create it digitally.

668
00:51:57,365 --> 00:52:00,910
{\an8}And it created this wonderful sense
of real magic,

669
00:52:00,994 --> 00:52:03,413
{\an8}but when the staircase moves
in other moments in the film,

670
00:52:03,496 --> 00:52:05,206
{\an8}and the kids are on the staircase,

671
00:52:05,290 --> 00:52:08,835
{\an8}we built a mechanical staircase
that moves from wall to wall.

672
00:52:09,669 --> 00:52:12,005
{\an8}GIRL 1: Look!
GIRL 2: Who's that girl?

673
00:52:12,088 --> 00:52:14,758
{\an8}MAN IN PICTURE:
Welcome to Hogwarts.

674
00:52:16,426 --> 00:52:17,510
GIRL 3:
Who's that?

675
00:52:30,774 --> 00:52:32,359
{\an8}Password?

676
00:52:32,817 --> 00:52:34,986
{\an8}Caput Draconis.

677
00:52:37,614 --> 00:52:39,407
Wow.

678
00:52:42,369 --> 00:52:46,414
PERCY: Follow me, everyone.
Keep up. Quickly, come on.

679
00:52:49,959 --> 00:52:51,711
Gather around here.

680
00:52:54,089 --> 00:52:56,633
Welcome to the Gryffindor
common room.

681
00:52:57,676 --> 00:53:02,055
Boys' dormitory is upstairs to the left.
Girls, the same on your right.

682
00:53:02,138 --> 00:53:05,350
Your belongings have
already been brought up.

683
00:54:13,543 --> 00:54:15,170
Made it!

684
00:54:15,378 --> 00:54:19,257
Can you imagine the look on old
McGonagall's face if we were late?

685
00:54:23,052 --> 00:54:28,016
- That was bloody brilliant!
- Thank you for that assessment.

686
00:54:28,099 --> 00:54:32,604
{\an8}It'd be better if I transfigured
Mr. Potter and you into a watch.

687
00:54:32,687 --> 00:54:36,065
{\an8}- Then one of you might be on time.
- We got lost.

688
00:54:36,149 --> 00:54:40,695
{\an8}Then perhaps a map? I trust you
don't need one to find your seats.

689
00:54:50,079 --> 00:54:55,084
There will be no foolish wand-waving
or silly incantations in this class.

690
00:54:55,835 --> 00:54:56,835
As such...

691
00:54:57,712 --> 00:54:59,756
...I don't expect many of you to appreciate...

692
00:54:59,839 --> 00:55:03,676
...the subtle science and exact art
that is potion-making.

693
00:55:03,760 --> 00:55:06,888
However, for those select few...

694
00:55:07,764 --> 00:55:11,184
...who possess the predisposition...

695
00:55:14,771 --> 00:55:18,191
...I can teach you
how to bewitch the mind...

696
00:55:18,274 --> 00:55:21,319
...and ensnare the senses.

697
00:55:21,402 --> 00:55:24,072
I can tell you how to bottle fame...

698
00:55:24,155 --> 00:55:30,078
...brew glory and even
put a stopper in death.

699
00:55:34,374 --> 00:55:39,128
Then again, maybe some of you have
come to Hogwarts with abilities...

700
00:55:39,212 --> 00:55:44,217
{\an8}...so formidable that
you feel confident enough...

701
00:55:44,300 --> 00:55:47,512
...to not pay attention.

702
00:55:54,310 --> 00:55:56,020
Mr. Potter.

703
00:55:58,106 --> 00:56:01,943
Our new celebrity.

704
00:56:04,070 --> 00:56:08,658
What would I get if I added root of
asphodel to an infusion of wormwood?

705
00:56:13,121 --> 00:56:15,665
You don't know? Let's try again.

706
00:56:15,748 --> 00:56:19,002
Where would you look
if I asked you to find a bezoar?

707
00:56:21,671 --> 00:56:23,172
I don't know, sir.

708
00:56:23,256 --> 00:56:26,759
SNAPE: What is the difference
between monkshood and wolfsbane?

709
00:56:29,762 --> 00:56:31,097
I don't know, sir.

710
00:56:33,099 --> 00:56:34,350
Pity.

711
00:56:36,102 --> 00:56:40,315
Clearly, fame isn't everything...

712
00:56:41,024 --> 00:56:42,567
...is it, Mr. Potter?

713
00:56:43,234 --> 00:56:45,278
Clearly, Hermione knows.

714
00:56:45,361 --> 00:56:47,196
Seems a pity not to ask her.

715
00:56:48,656 --> 00:56:50,116
SNAPE:
Silence.

716
00:57:01,461 --> 00:57:03,129
Put your hand down, you silly girl.

717
00:57:07,759 --> 00:57:09,802
For your information, Potter,

718
00:57:10,637 --> 00:57:13,389
asphodel and wormwood
make a sleeping potion so powerful

719
00:57:13,473 --> 00:57:16,142
it is known as
the Draught of the Living Dead.

720
00:57:16,225 --> 00:57:19,062
A bezoar is a stone
taken from the stomach of a goat

721
00:57:19,145 --> 00:57:21,648
and it will save you from most poisons.

722
00:57:21,731 --> 00:57:24,359
As for monkshood and wolfsbane,
they are the same plant,

723
00:57:24,442 --> 00:57:27,612
which also goes by the name of aconite.

724
00:57:29,948 --> 00:57:31,407
Well?

725
00:57:32,784 --> 00:57:35,954
Why aren't you all copying this down?

726
00:57:45,171 --> 00:57:47,298
And Gryffindors...

727
00:57:48,091 --> 00:57:52,553
note that five points will be taken
from your house

728
00:57:52,637 --> 00:57:55,682
for your classmate's cheek.

729
00:58:12,657 --> 00:58:17,286
<i>Eye of rabbit, harp string hum
Turn this water into rum</i>

730
00:58:19,205 --> 00:58:20,915
<i>Eye of rabbit...</i>

731
00:58:20,999 --> 00:58:24,002
What's Seamus trying to do
to the water?

732
00:58:24,085 --> 00:58:28,715
Turn it to rum. Actually managed
a weak tea yesterday, before--

733
00:58:28,798 --> 00:58:30,425
[EXPLODES]

734
00:58:33,594 --> 00:58:35,179
[OWL CRIES]

735
00:58:35,263 --> 00:58:37,473
Mail's here.

736
00:59:09,672 --> 00:59:12,717
Can I borrow this? Thanks.

737
00:59:16,596 --> 00:59:18,931
Look, Neville's got a Remembrall.

738
00:59:19,015 --> 00:59:24,562
{\an8}I've read about those. The smoke turns
red when you've forgotten something.

739
00:59:24,645 --> 00:59:28,316
{\an8}The problem is, I can't remember
what I've forgotten.

740
00:59:28,399 --> 00:59:33,154
{\an8}Somebody broke into Gringotts. Listen.

741
00:59:33,237 --> 00:59:36,824
{\an8}"Believed to be the work
of Dark wizards or witches...

742
00:59:36,908 --> 00:59:41,913
{\an8}...Gringotts goblins acknowledge
the breach but insist nothing was taken.

743
00:59:41,996 --> 00:59:47,794
{\an8}The vault in question, number 713,
had been emptied earlier that same day."

744
00:59:47,877 --> 00:59:51,672
{\an8}That's odd. That's the vault
Hagrid and I went to.

745
01:00:01,099 --> 01:00:04,977
{\an8}- Good afternoon, class.
- Good afternoon, Madam Hooch.

746
01:00:05,061 --> 01:00:07,897
{\an8}Good afternoon, Amanda.
Good afternoon.

747
01:00:09,148 --> 01:00:11,609
{\an8}Welcome to your first flying lesson.

748
01:00:11,692 --> 01:00:15,780
{\an8}What are you waiting for?
Step up to your broomstick.

749
01:00:15,863 --> 01:00:21,661
{\an8}Come on now, hurry up. Stick your hand
over the broom and say, "Up."

750
01:00:21,744 --> 01:00:23,204
Up!

751
01:00:23,287 --> 01:00:24,997
Up. Up.

752
01:00:25,081 --> 01:00:26,290
Wow!

753
01:00:26,374 --> 01:00:27,792
Up.

754
01:00:29,961 --> 01:00:31,671
Up. Up!

755
01:00:31,754 --> 01:00:33,840
With feeling.

756
01:00:33,923 --> 01:00:35,091
ALL:
Up!

757
01:00:35,174 --> 01:00:36,968
- Up. Up.
- Up. Up.

758
01:00:39,512 --> 01:00:41,514
Up! Oh!

759
01:00:42,348 --> 01:00:44,684
Shut up, Harry.

760
01:00:44,767 --> 01:00:49,522
Now, once you've got hold of
your broom, I want you to mount it.

761
01:00:49,605 --> 01:00:53,693
{\an8}Grip it tight. You don't wanna be
sliding off the end.

762
01:00:54,193 --> 01:00:59,115
{\an8}When I blow my whistle, I want you
to kick off from the ground, hard.

763
01:00:59,198 --> 01:01:03,161
{\an8}Keep your broom steady,
hover for a moment...

764
01:01:03,244 --> 01:01:06,622
{\an8}...then lean forward slightly
and touch back down.

765
01:01:07,665 --> 01:01:10,918
{\an8}On my whistle. Three, two...

766
01:01:13,296 --> 01:01:14,755
{\an8}Mr. Longbottom.

767
01:01:19,343 --> 01:01:22,305
- Mr. Longbottom!
- Down, down!

768
01:01:22,388 --> 01:01:23,723
Neville!

769
01:01:27,393 --> 01:01:29,687
Come back down this instant!

770
01:01:39,989 --> 01:01:41,866
Mr. Longbo--

771
01:01:44,076 --> 01:01:46,120
[NEVILLE SCREAMS]

772
01:01:51,167 --> 01:01:52,293
NEVILLE:
Whoa!

773
01:01:58,049 --> 01:01:59,050
Ow!

774
01:01:59,133 --> 01:02:00,801
MADAM HOOCH:
Everyone out of the way!

775
01:02:06,974 --> 01:02:08,559
Is he all right?

776
01:02:09,518 --> 01:02:15,274
Oh, dear, it's a broken wrist.
Poor boy. Come on now, up you get.

777
01:02:16,484 --> 01:02:21,280
Keep your feet on the ground
while I take him to the hospital wing.

778
01:02:21,364 --> 01:02:25,159
Understand? If I see
a single broom in the air...

779
01:02:25,243 --> 01:02:30,581
...the one riding it will be expelled
before they can say Quidditch.

780
01:02:30,748 --> 01:02:32,708
{\an8}Did you see his face?

781
01:02:32,792 --> 01:02:36,796
{\an8}If he had squeezed this, he'd have
remembered to fall on his arse.

782
01:02:36,879 --> 01:02:38,881
Give it here, Malfoy.

783
01:02:40,216 --> 01:02:44,053
{\an8}No. I'll leave it somewhere
for Longbottom to find.

784
01:02:48,057 --> 01:02:50,101
{\an8}How about on the roof?

785
01:02:51,727 --> 01:02:55,606
{\an8}What's the matter, Potter?
Bit beyond your reach?

786
01:02:58,192 --> 01:03:01,279
Harry, no way!
You heard what Madam Hooch said.

787
01:03:01,362 --> 01:03:03,948
Besides, you don't know how to fly.

788
01:03:05,324 --> 01:03:07,326
What an idiot.

789
01:03:10,579 --> 01:03:13,499
{\an8}Give it here or I'll
knock you off your broom!

790
01:03:14,292 --> 01:03:15,501
{\an8}Is that so?

791
01:03:19,588 --> 01:03:21,299
{\an8}Have it your way, then.

792
01:03:54,623 --> 01:03:57,710
{\an8}BOY 1: Nice going, Harry.
BOY 2: That was wicked, Harry!

793
01:03:58,461 --> 01:04:00,087
Harry Potter!

794
01:04:01,422 --> 01:04:02,590
Follow me.

795
01:04:15,144 --> 01:04:16,437
{\an8}You wait here.

796
01:04:19,148 --> 01:04:23,652
{\an8}Professor Quirrell, excuse me.
Could I borrow Wood for a moment?

797
01:04:24,653 --> 01:04:26,572
Yes, of course.

798
01:04:28,991 --> 01:04:31,369
[LIZARD GROWLS]

799
01:04:32,119 --> 01:04:38,000
Potter, this is Oliver Wood.
Wood, I have found you a Seeker.

800
01:04:40,127 --> 01:04:43,672
Have you heard? Harry Potter's
the new Gryffindor Seeker.

801
01:04:43,756 --> 01:04:46,008
I always knew he'd do well.

802
01:04:46,509 --> 01:04:50,471
Seeker? But first years
never make the house teams.

803
01:04:50,679 --> 01:04:55,601
- You must be the youngest player in--
- A century, McGonagall says.

804
01:04:55,684 --> 01:04:58,104
{\an8}Well done, Harry.
Wood's just told us.

805
01:04:58,187 --> 01:05:00,856
{\an8}Fred and George are on the team.
Beaters.

806
01:05:00,940 --> 01:05:04,777
{\an8}Our job is to make sure you
don't get bloodied up too bad.

807
01:05:04,860 --> 01:05:07,613
{\an8}Can't make any promises.
Rough game, Quidditch.

808
01:05:07,696 --> 01:05:11,826
But no one's died in years.
Someone vanishes occasionally.

809
01:05:11,909 --> 01:05:14,829
But they'll turn up in a month or two.

810
01:05:14,912 --> 01:05:20,626
Go on. Quidditch is great. Best game
there is, and you'll be great too.

811
01:05:20,709 --> 01:05:24,046
I've never played.
What if I make a fool of myself?

812
01:05:24,130 --> 01:05:27,925
{\an8}You won't make a fool of yourself.
It's in your blood.

813
01:05:34,890 --> 01:05:36,058
{\an8}Whoa.

814
01:05:36,225 --> 01:05:40,521
{\an8}Harry, you never told me your father
was a Seeker too.

815
01:05:41,355 --> 01:05:44,024
I didn't know.

816
01:05:49,071 --> 01:05:53,826
I'm telling you, it's spooky.
She knows more about you than you do.

817
01:05:53,909 --> 01:05:55,453
HARRY:
Who doesn't?

818
01:05:57,079 --> 01:05:58,622
What's happening?

819
01:05:59,457 --> 01:06:02,626
The staircases change, remember?

820
01:06:09,091 --> 01:06:12,845
{\an8}- Let's go this way.
RON: Before the staircase moves again.

821
01:06:21,187 --> 01:06:24,773
Does anybody feel like
we shouldn't be here?

822
01:06:24,899 --> 01:06:27,026
HERMIONE:
We're not supposed to be here.

823
01:06:27,109 --> 01:06:30,738
This is the third floor.
It's forbidden.

824
01:06:32,281 --> 01:06:33,991
Let's go.

825
01:06:34,074 --> 01:06:35,075
[CAT MEOWS]

826
01:06:36,035 --> 01:06:38,245
HERMIONE: It's Filch's cat!
HARRY: Run!

827
01:06:42,791 --> 01:06:45,878
{\an8}Quick, let's hide through that door!

828
01:06:51,258 --> 01:06:53,385
{\an8}- It's locked!
- We're done for!

829
01:06:53,511 --> 01:06:55,638
{\an8}Move over!

830
01:06:56,639 --> 01:06:58,766
<i>Alohomora.</i>

831
01:06:59,642 --> 01:07:00,768
{\an8}Get in.

832
01:07:02,811 --> 01:07:03,979
{\an8}<i>Alohomora?</i>

833
01:07:04,063 --> 01:07:06,732
{\an8}<i>Standard Book of Spells,</i>
chapter seven.

834
01:07:06,815 --> 01:07:09,652
{\an8}FILCH:
Anyone here, my sweet?

835
01:07:10,402 --> 01:07:11,737
{\an8}[CAT MEOWS]

836
01:07:16,534 --> 01:07:17,535
Come on.

837
01:07:18,285 --> 01:07:20,913
HERMIONE: Filch is gone.
- He thinks this door's locked.

838
01:07:20,996 --> 01:07:24,041
- It was locked.
- And for good reason.

839
01:07:50,359 --> 01:07:55,864
{\an8}What are they doing, keeping a thing
like that locked up in a school?

840
01:07:56,073 --> 01:07:59,702
{\an8}Didn't you see what
it was standing on?

841
01:07:59,785 --> 01:08:04,206
{\an8}I wasn't looking at its feet!
I was preoccupied with its heads.

842
01:08:04,290 --> 01:08:07,293
Or maybe you didn't notice.
There were three!

843
01:08:07,376 --> 01:08:11,213
HERMIONE: It was standing on
a trap door. It wasn't there by accident.

844
01:08:11,297 --> 01:08:14,883
- It's guarding something.
- Guarding something?

845
01:08:15,217 --> 01:08:19,138
That's right. Now, if you two
don't mind, I'm going to bed...

846
01:08:19,221 --> 01:08:22,933
...before you come up with another idea
to get us killed.

847
01:08:23,017 --> 01:08:25,644
Or worse, expelled.

848
01:08:29,398 --> 01:08:33,110
{\an8}She needs to sort out her priorities.

849
01:08:38,324 --> 01:08:42,578
Quidditch is easy to understand.
Each team has seven players.

850
01:08:42,661 --> 01:08:47,916
Three Chasers, two Beaters,
one Keeper and a Seeker. That's you.

851
01:08:53,547 --> 01:08:57,676
There are three kinds of balls.
This one's called the Quaffle.

852
01:08:57,760 --> 01:09:03,307
{\an8}The Chasers handle the Quaffle and try
to put it through one of those hoops.

853
01:09:04,058 --> 01:09:08,562
{\an8}The Keeper, that's me,
defends the hoops. With me so far?

854
01:09:08,646 --> 01:09:11,857
{\an8}I think so. What are those?

855
01:09:15,402 --> 01:09:16,570
You better take this.

856
01:09:27,623 --> 01:09:29,375
Careful now, it's coming back.

857
01:09:36,965 --> 01:09:40,678
Not bad, Potter.
You'd make a fair Beater.

858
01:09:42,805 --> 01:09:44,223
Uh-oh.

859
01:09:57,277 --> 01:09:59,071
What was that?

860
01:10:00,322 --> 01:10:04,076
Bludger. Nasty little buggers.

861
01:10:04,159 --> 01:10:07,162
But you are a Seeker.

862
01:10:11,333 --> 01:10:15,379
{\an8}The only thing I want you
to worry about is this.

863
01:10:16,213 --> 01:10:18,340
{\an8}The Golden Snitch.

864
01:10:19,216 --> 01:10:22,052
{\an8}- I like this ball.
- You like it now.

865
01:10:22,136 --> 01:10:26,265
Just wait. It's wicked fast
and damn near impossible to see.

866
01:10:26,348 --> 01:10:28,392
What do I do with it?

867
01:10:28,475 --> 01:10:31,937
You catch it.
Before the other team's Seeker.

868
01:10:32,020 --> 01:10:34,606
{\an8}You catch this, the game's over.

869
01:10:34,690 --> 01:10:37,901
{\an8}You catch this, Potter,
and we win.

870
01:10:44,783 --> 01:10:46,535
{\an8}Whoa.

871
01:10:47,703 --> 01:10:53,167
{\an8}One of a wizard's most rudimentary
skills is levitation...

872
01:10:53,250 --> 01:10:57,337
{\an8}...or the ability to make objects fly.

873
01:10:57,421 --> 01:10:59,965
{\an8}Do you have your feathers? Good.

874
01:11:00,048 --> 01:11:05,262
{\an8}Now, don't forget the nice wrist
movement we've been practicing.

875
01:11:05,345 --> 01:11:08,766
The swish and flick. Everyone.

876
01:11:09,308 --> 01:11:14,980
The swish and flick. Good.
Oh, and enunciate.

877
01:11:15,647 --> 01:11:19,943
<i>Wingardium Leviosa.</i>
Off you go, then.

878
01:11:20,986 --> 01:11:23,530
<i>Wingardium Leviosa.</i>

879
01:11:23,739 --> 01:11:26,074
{\an8}<i>Wingardium Leviosa.</i>

880
01:11:26,200 --> 01:11:29,745
{\an8}<i>Wingardium Leviosa.</i>

881
01:11:29,828 --> 01:11:34,291
{\an8}No, stop, stop, stop! You're going
to take someone's eye out.

882
01:11:34,374 --> 01:11:40,422
{\an8}Besides, you're saying it wrong.
It's <i>Leviosa,</i> not <i>Leviosar.</i>

883
01:11:40,923 --> 01:11:45,219
{\an8}You do it then, if you're so clever.
Go on, go on.

884
01:11:46,428 --> 01:11:49,515
{\an8}<i>Wingardium Leviosa.</i>

885
01:11:57,022 --> 01:12:02,736
{\an8}Well done! See here, everyone,
Miss Granger's done it!

886
01:12:02,820 --> 01:12:04,530
{\an8}Splendid!

887
01:12:06,114 --> 01:12:08,283
{\an8}Well done, dear.

888
01:12:08,450 --> 01:12:10,369
{\an8}[EXPLODES]

889
01:12:12,538 --> 01:12:16,625
I think we're going to need
another feather over here.

890
01:12:23,131 --> 01:12:27,511
"It's <i>Leviosa,</i> not <i>Leviosar."</i>

891
01:12:27,594 --> 01:12:32,307
She's a nightmare, honestly!
No wonder she hasn't got any friends.

892
01:12:33,642 --> 01:12:35,352
I think she heard you.

893
01:13:04,840 --> 01:13:06,842
{\an8}Where's Hermione?

894
01:13:07,134 --> 01:13:10,387
Parvati said she wouldn't
come out of the bathroom.

895
01:13:10,470 --> 01:13:14,600
She said that she'd been in there
all afternoon, crying.

896
01:13:18,979 --> 01:13:22,816
Troll in the dungeon!

897
01:13:22,900 --> 01:13:25,944
Troll in the dungeon!

898
01:13:29,031 --> 01:13:30,949
Thought you ought to know.

899
01:13:38,206 --> 01:13:41,168
Silence!

900
01:13:42,669 --> 01:13:45,839
Everyone will please not panic!

901
01:13:47,382 --> 01:13:48,508
Now...

902
01:13:49,176 --> 01:13:53,722
...prefects will lead their house
back to the dormitories.

903
01:13:54,431 --> 01:13:58,810
Teachers will follow me
to the dungeons.

904
01:14:10,238 --> 01:14:13,575
Gryffindors, keep up, please,
and stay alert.

905
01:14:13,659 --> 01:14:15,494
HARRY:
How could a troll get in?

906
01:14:15,577 --> 01:14:20,958
Not on its own. Trolls are really stupid.
Probably people playing jokes.

907
01:14:21,083 --> 01:14:24,419
- What?
- Hermione! She doesn't know.

908
01:14:34,513 --> 01:14:36,890
[GROWLS]

909
01:14:37,099 --> 01:14:39,559
I think the troll's left the dungeon.

910
01:14:44,231 --> 01:14:46,608
HARRY:
It's going into the girls' bathroom.

911
01:15:09,214 --> 01:15:11,591
{\an8}So, here we have the Mountain Troll
bathroom scene.

912
01:15:11,675 --> 01:15:12,968
{\an8}This was an interesting scene,

913
01:15:13,051 --> 01:15:16,221
because when Hermione is hiding from the troll
and the bathroom is smashing,

914
01:15:16,304 --> 01:15:17,889
we shot all of that practically.

915
01:15:17,973 --> 01:15:21,935
There were moments of the troll
that were tremendously fun.

916
01:15:22,019 --> 01:15:25,480
I love the disgusting quality
of the design of the troll.

917
01:15:25,564 --> 01:15:27,399
I think the troll was designed beautifully.

918
01:15:29,317 --> 01:15:31,403
Hey, pea brain!

919
01:15:41,163 --> 01:15:42,539
{\an8}[HERMIONE SCREAMS]

920
01:15:43,790 --> 01:15:44,833
Help!

921
01:15:44,916 --> 01:15:48,336
When Harry is sent up onto
the troll's shoulders,

922
01:15:48,420 --> 01:15:50,756
that's actually Dan being lifted up there.

923
01:15:50,839 --> 01:15:54,217
That is actually a CGI version of Harry

924
01:15:54,301 --> 01:15:55,761
riding on the troll's shoulders.

925
01:15:55,844 --> 01:15:57,596
It's an animated Harry Potter.

926
01:15:57,679 --> 01:16:00,974
If you freeze-frame some of these things
where he's being whipped around,

927
01:16:01,058 --> 01:16:06,730
you'll see that we, in a computer,
created a realistic version of Daniel Radcliffe.

928
01:16:06,855 --> 01:16:07,898
Do something!

929
01:16:07,981 --> 01:16:10,108
And this was one of
the more funny sequences to shoot,

930
01:16:10,192 --> 01:16:12,903
because Dan was being whisked out of frame

931
01:16:12,986 --> 01:16:15,363
and we're focusing back on Ron
in the sequence.

932
01:16:15,447 --> 01:16:18,992
And Dan was-- You know, all the blood
was rushing to his head at a certain point.

933
01:16:19,076 --> 01:16:22,329
But it's a very funny sequence,

934
01:16:22,412 --> 01:16:25,540
{\an8}and kids seem to really respond to it and love it.

935
01:16:25,624 --> 01:16:28,835
And I do love the character of the troll
when the troll is hit in the head.

936
01:16:28,919 --> 01:16:29,919
It's very funny.

937
01:16:31,129 --> 01:16:32,923
Cool.

938
01:16:57,531 --> 01:17:00,450
{\an8}Is it dead?

939
01:17:00,534 --> 01:17:03,870
I don't think so. Just knocked out.

940
01:17:09,835 --> 01:17:12,420
Ugh. Troll boogers.

941
01:17:15,465 --> 01:17:19,261
Oh, my goodness!
Explain yourselves, both of you!

942
01:17:19,344 --> 01:17:23,098
- Well, what it is--
- It's my fault, Professor McGonagall.

943
01:17:26,143 --> 01:17:27,394
Miss Granger?

944
01:17:28,228 --> 01:17:33,024
I went looking for the troll.
I thought I could handle it.

945
01:17:33,441 --> 01:17:35,527
But I was wrong.

946
01:17:35,610 --> 01:17:40,699
If Harry and Ron hadn't come
and found me, I'd probably be dead.

947
01:17:41,658 --> 01:17:46,079
McGONAGALL: Be that as it may,
it was an extremely foolish thing to do.

948
01:17:46,163 --> 01:17:51,585
I expected more rational behavior
and am very disappointed in you.

949
01:17:52,210 --> 01:17:55,172
Five points will be taken
from Gryffindor...

950
01:17:55,255 --> 01:17:58,216
...for your serious lack of judgment.

951
01:17:59,426 --> 01:18:01,636
As for you two gentlemen...

952
01:18:01,720 --> 01:18:04,389
...I just hope you realize
how fortunate you are.

953
01:18:05,265 --> 01:18:08,810
Not many first-year students
could take on a troll...

954
01:18:08,894 --> 01:18:11,104
...and live to tell the tale.

955
01:18:11,771 --> 01:18:14,191
Five points...

956
01:18:15,567 --> 01:18:18,028
...will be awarded to each of you...

957
01:18:20,280 --> 01:18:22,616
...for sheer dumb luck.

958
01:18:28,955 --> 01:18:32,042
Perhaps you ought to go.
It might wake up.

959
01:18:35,253 --> 01:18:37,339
[TROLL GROWLS]

960
01:18:42,219 --> 01:18:44,429
Good of you to get us
out of trouble like that.

961
01:18:44,512 --> 01:18:46,681
Mind you, we did save her life.

962
01:18:46,765 --> 01:18:50,810
Mind you, she might not have needed saving
if you hadn't insulted her.

963
01:18:51,645 --> 01:18:53,688
What are friends for?

964
01:18:57,150 --> 01:18:59,778
{\an8}RON:
Take a bit of toast, mate. Go on.

965
01:18:59,861 --> 01:19:03,490
{\an8}Ron's right.
You'll need your strength today.

966
01:19:03,573 --> 01:19:05,242
{\an8}I'm not hungry.

967
01:19:06,284 --> 01:19:12,165
{\an8}Good luck today, Potter.
You've proven yourself against a troll.

968
01:19:12,249 --> 01:19:15,460
{\an8}A game of Quidditch
should be easy work.

969
01:19:15,543 --> 01:19:18,046
{\an8}Even if it is against Slytherin.

970
01:19:26,388 --> 01:19:29,808
- That explains the blood.
- Blood?

971
01:19:30,267 --> 01:19:34,437
Last night, I'm guessing Snape let
the troll in as a diversion...

972
01:19:34,521 --> 01:19:37,399
...so he could get past that dog.

973
01:19:37,482 --> 01:19:40,402
But he got bit,
that's why he's limping.

974
01:19:40,485 --> 01:19:42,654
But why would anyone go near that dog?

975
01:19:43,363 --> 01:19:46,700
At Gringotts, Hagrid took
something out of the vault.

976
01:19:46,783 --> 01:19:49,035
Said it was Hogwarts business,
very secret.

977
01:19:50,245 --> 01:19:51,454
HERMIONE:
You're saying--

978
01:19:51,538 --> 01:19:54,791
That's what the dog's guarding.
That's what Snape wants.

979
01:19:54,874 --> 01:19:57,961
[OWL CRIES]

980
01:20:09,139 --> 01:20:13,184
- Bit early for mail, isn't it?
- But I never get mail.

981
01:20:13,768 --> 01:20:15,270
Let's open it.

982
01:20:25,488 --> 01:20:26,698
{\an8}HARRY:
It's a broomstick.

983
01:20:27,532 --> 01:20:31,661
That's not just a broomstick,
it's a Nimbus 2000!

984
01:20:33,121 --> 01:20:34,748
{\an8}But who--?

985
01:20:56,811 --> 01:20:59,397
- Scared, Harry?
- A little.

986
01:20:59,481 --> 01:21:03,276
It's all right. I felt the same way
before my first game.

987
01:21:03,360 --> 01:21:06,821
- What happened?
- I don't really remember.

988
01:21:07,197 --> 01:21:09,991
I took a Bludger to the head
two minutes in.

989
01:21:10,075 --> 01:21:11,826
Woke up in hospital a week later.

990
01:21:27,675 --> 01:21:32,347
{\an8}And here it is, the biggest challenge
of this particular film,

991
01:21:32,430 --> 01:21:36,017
{\an8}the question that more people were asking me
about as we were making the film:

992
01:21:36,101 --> 01:21:38,353
{\an8}How in God's name are you
going to do Quidditch?

993
01:21:38,436 --> 01:21:41,898
{\an8}Well, we worked on it a long time.

994
01:21:41,981 --> 01:21:47,404
{\an8}And I think part of our concern
was creating the stadium.

995
01:21:47,487 --> 01:21:51,950
{\an8}As written in the books, it was sort of
your typical stadium seating.

996
01:21:52,033 --> 01:21:54,577
{\an8}We wanted to create
an environment with towers.

997
01:21:54,661 --> 01:21:57,789
{\an8}Stuart Craig and I came up
with this idea of towers,

998
01:21:57,872 --> 01:22:02,335
{\an8}so Harry and the other Quidditch players
could fly around something,

999
01:22:02,419 --> 01:22:05,505
{\an8}and we would have something
in the foreground to create a sense of speed.

1000
01:22:05,588 --> 01:22:08,967
{\an8}You don't really have a sense of speed
when you just have the background moving.

1001
01:22:09,050 --> 01:22:11,469
{\an8}We actually needed those towers
in this sequence

1002
01:22:11,553 --> 01:22:13,304
{\an8}to create that sense of speed.

1003
01:22:13,388 --> 01:22:16,141
My dream is to see this sequence in 3D.

1004
01:22:16,224 --> 01:22:19,185
Someday, I would love to get the picture back

1005
01:22:19,269 --> 01:22:23,690
and actually restore it in a 3D version
to see it in an IMAX theater in 3D.

1006
01:22:23,773 --> 01:22:27,986
I think this would benefit in a big way
by seeing it in a 3D environment.

1007
01:22:28,069 --> 01:22:30,655
{\an8}It was important to me to also
teach the audience,

1008
01:22:30,738 --> 01:22:33,908
{\an8}those who were unfamiliar with the books,
the rules of Quidditch,

1009
01:22:33,992 --> 01:22:35,618
{\an8}which I had to learn myself.

1010
01:22:35,702 --> 01:22:39,289
{\an8}Reading the book six or seven times,
I never really understood all of the rules,

1011
01:22:39,372 --> 01:22:41,541
{\an8}so JK Rowling came up
with a chart for me.

1012
01:22:41,624 --> 01:22:44,752
{\an8}She basically gave me the rules of Quidditch,

1013
01:22:44,836 --> 01:22:47,922
{\an8}which I still have, so I was able
to incorporate those into the film.

1014
01:22:49,507 --> 01:22:51,509
{\an8}A lot of this we shot practically.

1015
01:22:51,593 --> 01:22:53,553
{\an8}But a lot of this is obviously CGI work.

1016
01:22:53,636 --> 01:22:56,639
{\an8}The only way to really get these kids
flying on broomsticks

1017
01:22:56,723 --> 01:22:58,516
{\an8}is to put them in a CGI environment.

1018
01:22:58,600 --> 01:23:01,895
So we would shoot Harry
and all the individual Quidditch players

1019
01:23:01,978 --> 01:23:03,730
on a separate green-screen stage,

1020
01:23:03,813 --> 01:23:06,191
and, using motion control cameras,

1021
01:23:06,274 --> 01:23:09,736
incorporate them into the backgrounds
of what we see here.

1022
01:23:10,612 --> 01:23:13,239
{\an8}I think that it was one of
the more grueling experiences

1023
01:23:13,323 --> 01:23:15,992
{\an8}for most of the actors
who were working in this sequence,

1024
01:23:16,075 --> 01:23:19,829
{\an8}because riding those brooms
was a tremendously difficult thing,

1025
01:23:19,913 --> 01:23:23,917
{\an8}to create a sense of movement,
to create a sense of urgency,

1026
01:23:24,000 --> 01:23:26,419
{\an8}and also I think, at the same time,

1027
01:23:26,503 --> 01:23:30,632
{\an8}to really feel as if these are
real athletes playing a game.

1028
01:23:30,715 --> 01:23:32,926
{\an8}And that was the biggest challenge for me.

1029
01:23:33,009 --> 01:23:35,094
{\an8}I wanted Quidditch to feel like a real sport.

1030
01:23:35,178 --> 01:23:36,804
I'm a big football and basketball fan,

1031
01:23:36,888 --> 01:23:40,517
and I wanted it to feel
like it was an exciting spectator sport

1032
01:23:40,600 --> 01:23:42,727
and one that would really
involve the audience.

1033
01:23:42,810 --> 01:23:46,189
{\an8}So, I think this particular
Quidditch sequence is a lot of fun,

1034
01:23:46,272 --> 01:23:48,733
{\an8}and, again, I hope to see it
in 3D some day.

1035
01:24:03,206 --> 01:24:06,793
- Yes!
- Another 10 points to Gryffindor!

1036
01:24:20,640 --> 01:24:22,141
{\an8}Give me that!

1037
01:24:53,923 --> 01:24:55,967
Take that side!

1038
01:25:43,765 --> 01:25:45,516
{\an8}Whoa. Whoa!

1039
01:25:46,059 --> 01:25:48,645
{\an8}HAGRID: What's going on
with Harry's broomstick?

1040
01:25:58,237 --> 01:26:00,573
It's Snape.
He's jinxing the broom!

1041
01:26:00,657 --> 01:26:04,327
- Jinxing the broom? What do we do?
- Leave it to me.

1042
01:26:26,808 --> 01:26:28,267
Come on, Hermione!

1043
01:26:42,448 --> 01:26:45,410
<i>Lacarnum Inflamarae.</i>

1044
01:26:53,292 --> 01:26:56,254
MAN:
Fire! You're on fire!

1045
01:27:14,188 --> 01:27:16,274
{\an8}Go, go, go, go!

1046
01:28:08,367 --> 01:28:10,453
Looks like he's gonna be sick.

1047
01:28:11,788 --> 01:28:13,372
LEE:
He's got the Snitch!

1048
01:28:13,456 --> 01:28:17,668
Harry Potter receives 150 points
for catching the Snitch!

1049
01:28:17,752 --> 01:28:19,420
Gryffindor wins!

1050
01:28:23,007 --> 01:28:25,510
Oh, no.

1051
01:28:28,304 --> 01:28:29,555
Yes!

1052
01:29:03,089 --> 01:29:07,260
{\an8}Nonsense! Why would Snape
put a curse on Harry's broom?

1053
01:29:07,343 --> 01:29:11,514
{\an8}Who knows? Why was he trying
to get past that three-headed dog?

1054
01:29:11,597 --> 01:29:14,100
{\an8}- Who told you about Fluffy?
- Fluffy?

1055
01:29:14,183 --> 01:29:17,979
{\an8}- That thing has a name?
- Of course he has a name. He's mine.

1056
01:29:18,062 --> 01:29:22,733
{\an8}I bought him off an Irishman.
I lent him to Dumbledore to guard--

1057
01:29:22,817 --> 01:29:23,860
Yes?

1058
01:29:23,943 --> 01:29:28,155
Shouldn't have said that.
No more questions! That's top-secret.

1059
01:29:28,781 --> 01:29:32,910
But whatever Fluffy's guarding,
Snape's trying to steal it.

1060
01:29:32,994 --> 01:29:36,998
Codswallop. Professor Snape
is a Hogwarts teacher.

1061
01:29:37,081 --> 01:29:42,086
Teacher or not, I know a spell when
I see one. I've read all about them.

1062
01:29:42,169 --> 01:29:45,965
You've got to keep eye contact,
and Snape wasn't blinking.

1063
01:29:46,048 --> 01:29:48,009
Exactly.

1064
01:29:48,968 --> 01:29:51,762
{\an8}Now, you listen to me,
all three of you.

1065
01:29:51,846 --> 01:29:56,601
{\an8}You're meddling in things that ought
not to be meddled in. It's dangerous.

1066
01:29:56,684 --> 01:30:01,147
{\an8}What that dog is guarding is between
Dumbledore and Nicolas Flamel.

1067
01:30:02,106 --> 01:30:03,482
Nicolas Flamel?

1068
01:30:04,525 --> 01:30:09,280
I shouldn't have said that.
I should not have said that.

1069
01:30:09,363 --> 01:30:13,534
Nicolas Flamel.
Who's Nicolas Flamel?

1070
01:30:13,618 --> 01:30:15,745
I don't know.

1071
01:30:34,597 --> 01:30:37,600
<i>Merry Christmas
Merry Christmas</i>

1072
01:30:37,683 --> 01:30:40,436
<i>Ring the Hogwart bell</i>

1073
01:30:40,645 --> 01:30:43,439
<i>Merry Christmas
Merry Christmas</i>

1074
01:30:43,689 --> 01:30:46,609
<i>Cast a Christmas spell</i>

1075
01:31:00,206 --> 01:31:02,917
Knight to e5.

1076
01:31:11,217 --> 01:31:13,302
Queen to e5.

1077
01:31:18,933 --> 01:31:20,393
That's totally barbaric!

1078
01:31:21,060 --> 01:31:24,647
{\an8}That's wizard's chess.
I see you've packed.

1079
01:31:24,730 --> 01:31:26,190
{\an8}I see you haven't.

1080
01:31:26,607 --> 01:31:31,779
{\an8}Change of plans. My parents went
to Romania to visit my brother Charlie.

1081
01:31:31,862 --> 01:31:35,908
{\an8}- He's studying dragons there.
- Good. You can help Harry.

1082
01:31:35,992 --> 01:31:39,537
{\an8}He's going to the library
to look up Nicolas Flamel.

1083
01:31:39,620 --> 01:31:42,373
We've looked a hundred times!

1084
01:31:43,749 --> 01:31:48,337
Not in the restricted section.
Happy Christmas.

1085
01:31:51,215 --> 01:31:54,093
I think we've had
a bad influence on her.

1086
01:31:56,679 --> 01:32:00,349
RON: Harry, wake up!
Come on, Harry, wake up!

1087
01:32:10,860 --> 01:32:14,196
- Happy Christmas, Harry.
- Happy Christmas, Ron.

1088
01:32:14,280 --> 01:32:16,198
What are you wearing?

1089
01:32:17,199 --> 01:32:20,828
{\an8}Oh, my mum made it.
Looks like you've got one too.

1090
01:32:21,954 --> 01:32:24,415
{\an8}- I've got presents?
- Yeah.

1091
01:32:31,881 --> 01:32:33,632
RON:
There they are.

1092
01:32:44,977 --> 01:32:48,481
{\an8}"Your father left this
in my possession before he died.

1093
01:32:48,564 --> 01:32:52,777
{\an8}It is time it was returned to you.
Use it well."

1094
01:33:04,413 --> 01:33:07,625
{\an8}So this was another challenging sequence.

1095
01:33:07,708 --> 01:33:11,003
{\an8}Harry gets his invisibility cloak.

1096
01:33:11,087 --> 01:33:14,090
{\an8}It wasn't particularly challenging
to make Harry disappear.

1097
01:33:14,173 --> 01:33:17,301
{\an8}We just had Daniel put on a green cloak.

1098
01:33:17,384 --> 01:33:19,553
{\an8}And then we were able
to erase part of his body.

1099
01:33:19,637 --> 01:33:22,056
{\an8}But the big challenge here

1100
01:33:22,139 --> 01:33:24,850
{\an8}was really how we were going to depict Harry

1101
01:33:24,934 --> 01:33:28,521
{\an8}walking through the library
later in the sequence

1102
01:33:28,604 --> 01:33:30,523
{\an8}and see the cloak around him.

1103
01:33:30,606 --> 01:33:33,984
{\an8}How does an audience member accept that

1104
01:33:34,068 --> 01:33:37,613
{\an8}when we're introducing
the concept of invisibility?

1105
01:33:37,696 --> 01:33:40,908
{\an8}So what we did, we actually shot,
which you will see later,

1106
01:33:40,991 --> 01:33:47,998
{\an8}Daniel Radcliffe underneath
sort of a gauze, lace version of the cloak.

1107
01:33:48,082 --> 01:33:51,836
{\an8}And it seems completely inconsistent stylistically

1108
01:33:51,919 --> 01:33:54,046
{\an8}with the concept of invisibility.

1109
01:33:54,130 --> 01:33:58,134
{\an8}But when you see him walking
with this cloak over him,

1110
01:33:58,217 --> 01:34:00,219
{\an8}you immediately buy that concept.

1111
01:34:00,302 --> 01:34:06,142
{\an8}And this was a very, very tense day
of shooting for me,

1112
01:34:06,225 --> 01:34:09,645
{\an8}because we were allowed into this library,
the Bodleian Library.

1113
01:34:09,770 --> 01:34:14,358
{\an8}And all of these books you see are
hundreds and hundreds of years old, one of a kind.

1114
01:34:14,441 --> 01:34:16,402
{\an8}So we really had to be very careful.

1115
01:34:16,485 --> 01:34:21,907
{\an8}It was the first film in a long time that
was permitted to shoot in this particular library.

1116
01:34:21,991 --> 01:34:27,454
{\an8}When Harry-- One of the biggest moments
for the audience ironically in this film,

1117
01:34:27,538 --> 01:34:29,582
{\an8}which is a small moment, really, in the books,

1118
01:34:29,665 --> 01:34:33,586
{\an8}is when he opens this first book
and this face pops out of the book.

1119
01:34:33,669 --> 01:34:36,964
{\an8}We did that with digital effects,
but it works really well.

1120
01:34:37,047 --> 01:34:39,133
{\an8}But the audience jumped out of their seats.

1121
01:34:39,216 --> 01:34:43,554
{\an8}The kids particularly weren't expecting
that kind of scare at that particular time.

1122
01:34:45,139 --> 01:34:46,974
{\an8}So, again, we had to shoot this sequence

1123
01:34:47,057 --> 01:34:49,602
{\an8}within five hours, I think, on a Sunday.

1124
01:34:49,685 --> 01:34:53,189
{\an8}Because it was the only time anyone
had been permitted into this library.

1125
01:34:56,901 --> 01:34:59,570
Oh, we've got our friend Filch
coming in here.

1126
01:34:59,653 --> 01:35:03,741
And this guy, David Bradley,
one of the great faces of British actors.

1127
01:35:03,824 --> 01:35:04,825
I just loved him.

1128
01:35:04,909 --> 01:35:08,412
He seemed like he stepped out
of an old David Lean picture, you know?

1129
01:35:08,495 --> 01:35:11,457
He looks like one of those guys
in <i>Great Expectations</i> or <i>Oliver Twist,</i>

1130
01:35:11,540 --> 01:35:13,500
and then his voice with the stringy hair.

1131
01:35:13,584 --> 01:35:16,128
I used to read this book as a kid,
this comic called <i>Creepy.</i>

1132
01:35:16,212 --> 01:35:19,757
{\an8}And he looked a little like Uncle Creepy.
I just love David Bradley.

1133
01:35:19,840 --> 01:35:21,217
{\an8}He's a fantastic actor.

1134
01:35:34,647 --> 01:35:36,482
{\an8}[CAT MEOWS]

1135
01:35:50,496 --> 01:35:51,872
{\an8}QUIRRELL:
Severus, I...

1136
01:35:52,539 --> 01:35:56,502
You don't want me
as your enemy, Quirrell.

1137
01:35:56,585 --> 01:35:59,964
- I don't know what you mean.
- You know perfectly well what I mean.

1138
01:36:18,565 --> 01:36:21,360
{\an8}We'll have another little chat soon.

1139
01:36:21,986 --> 01:36:27,574
{\an8}When you've had time to decide
where your loyalties lie.

1140
01:36:27,658 --> 01:36:32,121
Professors. I found this
in the restricted section.

1141
01:36:32,621 --> 01:36:37,459
It's still hot. That means
there's a student out of bed.

1142
01:38:09,718 --> 01:38:11,220
{\an8}Mum?

1143
01:38:14,890 --> 01:38:16,392
{\an8}Dad?

1144
01:38:51,635 --> 01:38:55,722
HARRY: Ron, you've really gotta
see this! Ron, you've gotta see this!

1145
01:38:58,434 --> 01:39:01,437
Ron, come on, get out of bed!

1146
01:39:01,520 --> 01:39:05,023
- Why?
- There's something you've got to see!

1147
01:39:11,780 --> 01:39:15,409
{\an8}Come on! Come!
Come look, it's my parents!

1148
01:39:17,578 --> 01:39:19,538
{\an8}I only see us.

1149
01:39:19,788 --> 01:39:22,124
{\an8}Look in properly.
Go on, stand there.

1150
01:39:23,208 --> 01:39:29,173
{\an8}- There. You see them, don't you?
- That's me! Only I'm head boy.

1151
01:39:29,673 --> 01:39:32,050
{\an8}And I'm holding the Quidditch Cup.

1152
01:39:32,176 --> 01:39:36,388
{\an8}And bloody hell!
I'm Quidditch captain too!

1153
01:39:37,556 --> 01:39:39,391
{\an8}I look good.

1154
01:39:40,642 --> 01:39:44,480
{\an8}Harry, do you think this mirror
shows the future?

1155
01:39:44,563 --> 01:39:48,942
{\an8}How can it?
Both my parents are dead.

1156
01:40:10,756 --> 01:40:12,132
How about yours, Ron?

1157
01:40:16,929 --> 01:40:20,224
- Ron?
- I'll be right back.

1158
01:40:30,984 --> 01:40:32,611
Want to play chess?

1159
01:40:33,403 --> 01:40:36,156
- No.
- Want to go and visit Hagrid?

1160
01:40:37,115 --> 01:40:38,408
No.

1161
01:40:38,992 --> 01:40:42,663
Harry, I know what you're thinking, but don't.

1162
01:40:42,746 --> 01:40:45,791
There's something not right about that mirror.

1163
01:41:08,522 --> 01:41:10,691
{\an8}Back again, Harry?

1164
01:41:13,819 --> 01:41:16,363
{\an8}I see that you,
like many before you...

1165
01:41:16,446 --> 01:41:19,700
{\an8}...have discovered the delights
of the Mirror of Erised.

1166
01:41:21,034 --> 01:41:25,205
I trust by now
you realize what it does.

1167
01:41:26,498 --> 01:41:29,042
Let me give you a clue.

1168
01:41:29,543 --> 01:41:31,795
The happiest man on earth...

1169
01:41:31,878 --> 01:41:35,299
...would look in the mirror
and see only himself...

1170
01:41:35,382 --> 01:41:37,843
...exactly as he is.

1171
01:41:37,926 --> 01:41:43,181
So then, it shows us what we want.
Whatever we want.

1172
01:41:43,265 --> 01:41:46,018
Yes. And no.

1173
01:41:47,060 --> 01:41:49,646
It shows us nothing more or less...

1174
01:41:49,730 --> 01:41:55,193
...than the deepest and most desperate
desires of our hearts.

1175
01:41:55,944 --> 01:41:59,406
Now you, Harry, who have
never known your family...

1176
01:42:00,866 --> 01:42:04,870
...you see them standing beside you.

1177
01:42:04,953 --> 01:42:07,497
But remember this, Harry.

1178
01:42:07,581 --> 01:42:13,503
This mirror gives us
neither knowledge...

1179
01:42:13,587 --> 01:42:15,422
...or truth.

1180
01:42:16,757 --> 01:42:22,137
Men have wasted away in front of it.
Even gone mad.

1181
01:42:23,889 --> 01:42:28,101
That is why tomorrow
it will be moved to a new home.

1182
01:42:28,185 --> 01:42:30,145
And I must ask you...

1183
01:42:31,104 --> 01:42:34,358
...not to go looking for it again.

1184
01:42:35,734 --> 01:42:38,820
It does not do to dwell on dreams...

1185
01:42:39,446 --> 01:42:41,823
...and forget to live.

1186
01:43:38,088 --> 01:43:39,339
Hi, Hedwig.

1187
01:43:42,050 --> 01:43:44,428
Look at you, playing with your cards.

1188
01:43:44,511 --> 01:43:45,512
Pathetic.

1189
01:43:46,138 --> 01:43:48,557
We've got final exams coming up soon.

1190
01:43:48,640 --> 01:43:51,143
I'm ready. Ask me any question.

1191
01:43:51,226 --> 01:43:55,021
All right. What's the three most crucial ingredients
in a Forgetfulness Potion?

1192
01:43:55,772 --> 01:43:57,149
I forgot.

1193
01:43:57,232 --> 01:44:00,277
And what, may I ask, do you plan to do
if this comes up in the final exam?

1194
01:44:00,360 --> 01:44:02,487
- Copy off you?
- No, you won't.

1195
01:44:02,571 --> 01:44:04,948
Besides, according to Professor McGonagall,

1196
01:44:05,031 --> 01:44:08,660
we're to be given special quills
bewitched with an anti-cheating spell.

1197
01:44:08,744 --> 01:44:10,287
That's insulting!

1198
01:44:10,370 --> 01:44:12,247
It's as if they don't trust us.

1199
01:44:12,330 --> 01:44:14,374
Dumbledore again!

1200
01:44:16,918 --> 01:44:18,587
[STUDENTS LAUGHING]

1201
01:44:18,670 --> 01:44:20,589
Leg-Locker Curse?

1202
01:44:20,672 --> 01:44:21,923
Malfoy.

1203
01:44:27,929 --> 01:44:31,183
You have got to start
standing up to people, Neville.

1204
01:44:31,266 --> 01:44:34,436
How? I can barely stand at all.

1205
01:44:35,187 --> 01:44:37,189
I'll do the counter-curse!

1206
01:44:37,272 --> 01:44:41,109
No, that's all I need--
you to set my bloody kneecaps on fire.

1207
01:44:42,027 --> 01:44:45,280
I don't appreciate the insinuation, Longbottom.

1208
01:44:45,363 --> 01:44:51,828
Besides, if anyone cares to notice,
my eyebrows have completely grown back.

1209
01:44:56,750 --> 01:44:58,001
I found him!

1210
01:44:58,835 --> 01:45:04,049
"Dumbledore is particularly famous for his defeat
of the Dark Wizard Grindelwald in 1945--"

1211
01:45:04,132 --> 01:45:07,552
{\an8}- Go on.
- "for his discovery of the 12 uses of dragon blood,

1212
01:45:07,636 --> 01:45:10,972
{\an8}and his work on alchemy
with his partner Nicolas Flamel!"

1213
01:45:11,056 --> 01:45:14,434
HARRY: I knew the name sounded familiar.
I read it on the train that day.

1214
01:45:14,518 --> 01:45:15,769
Follow me!

1215
01:45:20,774 --> 01:45:24,361
Hey, wait! Where are you going?

1216
01:45:26,321 --> 01:45:28,240
What about the counter-curse?

1217
01:45:30,659 --> 01:45:35,872
I had you looking in the wrong section.
How could I be so stupid?

1218
01:45:36,790 --> 01:45:40,252
I checked this out weeks ago
for a bit of light reading.

1219
01:45:40,335 --> 01:45:42,212
This is light?

1220
01:45:46,633 --> 01:45:48,969
Of course! Here it is!

1221
01:45:49,469 --> 01:45:53,473
Nicolas Flamel is the only known
maker of the Philosopher's Stone.

1222
01:45:53,557 --> 01:45:54,850
The what?

1223
01:45:55,350 --> 01:45:58,019
Honestly, don't you two read?

1224
01:45:58,937 --> 01:46:03,191
"The Philosopher's Stone is a legendary
substance with astonishing powers.

1225
01:46:03,275 --> 01:46:06,027
It'll transform any metal
into pure gold...

1226
01:46:06,111 --> 01:46:10,240
...and produces the Elixir of Life,
which will make the drinker immortal."

1227
01:46:10,323 --> 01:46:12,701
- Immortal?
- It means you'll never die.

1228
01:46:12,784 --> 01:46:14,953
I know what it means!

1229
01:46:15,662 --> 01:46:20,500
"The only Stone currently in existence
belongs to Mr. Nicolas Flamel...

1230
01:46:20,584 --> 01:46:25,881
...the noted alchemist who last year
celebrated his 665th birthday."

1231
01:46:27,591 --> 01:46:29,759
That's what Fluffy's guarding.

1232
01:46:29,843 --> 01:46:32,679
That's what's under the trap door.
The Philosopher's Stone.

1233
01:46:46,902 --> 01:46:48,403
[KNOCKING]

1234
01:46:51,448 --> 01:46:55,368
Don't wish to be rude,
but I'm in no state to entertain.

1235
01:46:55,452 --> 01:46:57,579
ALL:
We know about the Philosopher's Stone.

1236
01:46:59,331 --> 01:47:00,332
Oh.

1237
01:47:02,834 --> 01:47:07,964
- We think Snape's trying to steal it.
- Are you still on about him?

1238
01:47:08,048 --> 01:47:11,092
We know he's after it.
We don't know why.

1239
01:47:11,176 --> 01:47:15,221
Snape is one of the teachers
protecting the Stone. He won't steal it.

1240
01:47:15,680 --> 01:47:16,848
{\an8}What?

1241
01:47:16,932 --> 01:47:20,477
{\an8}You heard. Come on,
I'm a bit preoccupied today.

1242
01:47:20,560 --> 01:47:23,480
{\an8}HARRY: Wait a minute.
"One of the teachers"?

1243
01:47:23,563 --> 01:47:27,442
{\an8}There are other things
defending the Stone, aren't there?

1244
01:47:27,609 --> 01:47:30,236
{\an8}- Spells, enchantments.
HAGRID: Right.

1245
01:47:30,487 --> 01:47:33,698
Waste of bloody time, if you ask me.

1246
01:47:33,782 --> 01:47:35,867
Ain't no one gonna get past Fluffy.

1247
01:47:36,076 --> 01:47:39,663
Ain't a soul knows how,
except for me and Dumbledore.

1248
01:47:39,955 --> 01:47:43,667
I shouldn't have told you that.
I should not have told you that.

1249
01:47:43,750 --> 01:47:45,919
[RATTLING]

1250
01:47:57,347 --> 01:48:02,477
- Hagrid, what exactly is that?
- That? It's...

1251
01:48:02,686 --> 01:48:04,688
I know what that is!

1252
01:48:04,938 --> 01:48:07,565
But, Hagrid, how did you get one?

1253
01:48:07,941 --> 01:48:11,194
I won it. Off a stranger
I met down at the pub.

1254
01:48:11,361 --> 01:48:14,447
Seemed quite glad to be rid of it,
as a matter of fact.

1255
01:48:37,721 --> 01:48:39,889
Is that...

1256
01:48:40,724 --> 01:48:41,891
...a dragon?

1257
01:48:42,100 --> 01:48:46,521
That's not just a dragon.
That's a Norwegian Ridgeback.

1258
01:48:46,730 --> 01:48:49,607
My brother works
with these in Romania.

1259
01:48:49,816 --> 01:48:54,696
Isn't he beautiful? Oh, bless him.
Look, he knows his mummy.

1260
01:48:55,363 --> 01:48:57,157
Hello, Norbert.

1261
01:48:57,323 --> 01:49:00,869
- Norbert?
- He's gotta have a name, don't he?

1262
01:49:02,662 --> 01:49:04,456
{\an8}Don't you, Norbert?

1263
01:49:11,921 --> 01:49:15,091
{\an8}He'll have to be trained up a bit,
of course.

1264
01:49:16,634 --> 01:49:18,053
{\an8}[DRAGON CRIES]

1265
01:49:18,928 --> 01:49:21,056
Who's that?

1266
01:49:22,640 --> 01:49:23,808
Malfoy.

1267
01:49:25,560 --> 01:49:27,062
Oh, dear.

1268
01:49:28,605 --> 01:49:33,526
HARRY: Hagrid always wanted a dragon.
Told me so the first time I met him.

1269
01:49:33,610 --> 01:49:37,864
RON: It's crazy.
And worse, Malfoy knows.

1270
01:49:37,947 --> 01:49:42,160
HARRY: I don't understand. Is that bad?
- It's bad.

1271
01:49:42,243 --> 01:49:43,995
Good evening.

1272
01:49:48,124 --> 01:49:51,169
Nothing, I repeat, nothing...

1273
01:49:51,252 --> 01:49:55,006
...gives a student the right
to walk about at night.

1274
01:49:55,090 --> 01:49:59,886
{\an8}Therefore, as punishment for your
actions, 50 points will be taken.

1275
01:50:00,095 --> 01:50:02,430
{\an8}- 50?!
- Each.

1276
01:50:03,473 --> 01:50:05,809
{\an8}To ensure it doesn't happen again...

1277
01:50:06,059 --> 01:50:08,978
{\an8}...all four of you
will receive detention.

1278
01:50:10,313 --> 01:50:13,358
Excuse me, professor,
perhaps I heard you wrong.

1279
01:50:13,441 --> 01:50:15,860
I thought you said the four of us.

1280
01:50:15,944 --> 01:50:18,571
No, you heard me correctly.

1281
01:50:18,655 --> 01:50:23,827
Honorable as your intentions were,
you too were out of bed after hours.

1282
01:50:24,369 --> 01:50:27,163
You will join your classmates
in detention.

1283
01:50:38,341 --> 01:50:41,845
FILCH: A pity they let
the old punishments die.

1284
01:50:42,637 --> 01:50:47,308
Was a time detention found you
hanging by your thumbs in the dungeons.

1285
01:50:47,517 --> 01:50:50,353
God, I miss the screaming.

1286
01:50:52,856 --> 01:50:56,192
You'll be serving detention
with Hagrid tonight.

1287
01:50:56,359 --> 01:51:01,739
He's got a little job to do
inside the Dark Forest.

1288
01:51:03,825 --> 01:51:06,786
A sorry lot, this, Hagrid.

1289
01:51:08,246 --> 01:51:13,251
Good God, you're not still on
about that bloody dragon, are you?

1290
01:51:15,503 --> 01:51:17,547
Norbert's gone.

1291
01:51:18,131 --> 01:51:21,676
Dumbledore sent him off to Romania
to live in a colony.

1292
01:51:21,968 --> 01:51:25,221
{\an8}That's good, isn't it?
He's with his own kind.

1293
01:51:25,388 --> 01:51:28,016
{\an8}What if he don't like Romania?

1294
01:51:28,099 --> 01:51:32,729
{\an8}What if the other dragons are mean
to him? He's only a baby.

1295
01:51:32,812 --> 01:51:38,067
For God's sake, pull yourself together.
You're going into the Forest.

1296
01:51:38,276 --> 01:51:40,653
Got to have your wits about you.

1297
01:51:40,862 --> 01:51:46,534
The Forest? I thought that was a joke.
We can't go in there.

1298
01:51:46,993 --> 01:51:50,580
Students aren't allowed.
And there are...

1299
01:51:50,747 --> 01:51:51,789
[WOLF HOWLS]

1300
01:51:52,373 --> 01:51:53,583
...werewolves.

1301
01:51:54,042 --> 01:51:57,337
There's more than werewolves
in those trees.

1302
01:51:57,545 --> 01:51:59,047
You can be sure of that.

1303
01:52:02,175 --> 01:52:03,593
Nighty-night.

1304
01:52:06,179 --> 01:52:09,015
Right. Let's go.

1305
01:52:41,214 --> 01:52:42,966
[WOLF HOWLS]

1306
01:52:47,220 --> 01:52:49,681
Hagrid, what is that?

1307
01:52:49,889 --> 01:52:53,226
What we're here for.
See that?

1308
01:52:53,726 --> 01:52:59,107
That's unicorn blood, that is.
I found one dead a few weeks ago.

1309
01:52:59,649 --> 01:53:04,320
Now, this one's been hurt bad
by something.

1310
01:53:04,445 --> 01:53:07,115
[LEAVES RUSTLING]

1311
01:53:11,869 --> 01:53:17,583
So, it's our job to go
and find the poor beast.

1312
01:53:17,667 --> 01:53:20,878
- Ron, Hermione, come with me.
- Okay.

1313
01:53:21,296 --> 01:53:24,173
And, Harry, you'll go with Malfoy.

1314
01:53:25,842 --> 01:53:27,719
Okay. Then I get Fang.

1315
01:53:28,303 --> 01:53:33,349
Fine. Just so you know,
he's a bloody coward.

1316
01:53:33,433 --> 01:53:36,144
[FANG WHINES]

1317
01:53:37,895 --> 01:53:42,817
Wait till my father hears
about this. This is servant's stuff.

1318
01:53:42,900 --> 01:53:45,570
{\an8}If I didn't know better,
I'd say you were scared.

1319
01:53:45,737 --> 01:53:47,864
{\an8}All right, here we are in the Forbidden Forest.

1320
01:53:47,947 --> 01:53:51,701
{\an8}Now, this is an interesting sequence
because we actually shot

1321
01:53:51,784 --> 01:53:55,663
{\an8}the beginning of the sequence
in a real forest outside of London,

1322
01:53:55,747 --> 01:54:01,711
{\an8}and shot at night, filled it with fog,
and really wanted to create this sense of mystery.

1323
01:54:01,794 --> 01:54:04,464
{\an8}And as we get further into the forest,

1324
01:54:04,547 --> 01:54:08,134
{\an8}we move onto a set
that we built on the Leavesden soundstage.

1325
01:54:08,217 --> 01:54:10,303
{\an8}It was a fairly big set.

1326
01:54:10,386 --> 01:54:12,055
{\an8}It was very impressive, actually.

1327
01:54:12,138 --> 01:54:14,515
{\an8}We brought in all these real trees,
all these roots.

1328
01:54:14,599 --> 01:54:16,267
{\an8}And Stuart Craig, again, outdid himself

1329
01:54:16,351 --> 01:54:18,936
{\an8}because this feels like
a very, very real location.

1330
01:54:19,020 --> 01:54:23,316
{\an8}This is the first time
that Harry encounters Voldemort.

1331
01:54:23,399 --> 01:54:27,820
{\an8}Well, who we know is Quirrell
later in the picture.

1332
01:54:27,904 --> 01:54:30,907
{\an8}But drinking unicorn blood,
and this proved to be a challenge

1333
01:54:30,990 --> 01:54:34,077
because unicorn blood
is supposed to be silver.

1334
01:54:34,160 --> 01:54:37,663
Obviously we couldn't put mercury
in anyone's mouth.

1335
01:54:37,747 --> 01:54:41,376
And that's the only liquid
that has that metallic look.

1336
01:54:41,459 --> 01:54:46,881
{\an8}So what we did is we put
green liquid in our actor's mouth

1337
01:54:46,964 --> 01:54:49,133
{\an8}and then we changed it
to that silvery sort of look.

1338
01:54:49,217 --> 01:54:53,096
{\an8}Again, as you can probably tell,
this was done practically

1339
01:54:53,179 --> 01:54:57,016
with an actor on wires
who stood up and walked close to Harry.

1340
01:54:57,100 --> 01:54:58,540
At this point, we didn't really have

1341
01:54:58,601 --> 01:55:01,437
a definitive idea of what Voldemort
was gonna look like.

1342
01:55:01,562 --> 01:55:05,483
And I thought it was more frightening for
the audience if they didn't see his face at this point.

1343
01:55:05,566 --> 01:55:07,568
{\an8}This was a very scary scene.

1344
01:55:07,652 --> 01:55:11,614
{\an8}This first part was really done
without the benefit of visual effects,

1345
01:55:11,697 --> 01:55:13,991
{\an8}and then, of course,
the centaur comes into the scene.

1346
01:55:15,326 --> 01:55:16,744
[HOOVES BEATING]

1347
01:55:35,930 --> 01:55:41,436
Harry Potter, you must leave.
You are known to many creatures here.

1348
01:55:41,644 --> 01:55:45,648
The Forest is not safe at this time.
Especially for you.

1349
01:55:45,815 --> 01:55:48,609
What was that thing you saved me from?

1350
01:55:48,818 --> 01:55:54,157
A monstrous creature.
It is a terrible crime to slay a unicorn.

1351
01:55:54,323 --> 01:55:59,996
{\an8}Drinking its blood will keep you alive
even if you are an inch from death.

1352
01:56:00,079 --> 01:56:05,168
{\an8}But at a terrible price. For you
have slain something so pure...

1353
01:56:05,418 --> 01:56:10,256
{\an8}...that the moment the blood touches
your lips, you will have a half-life.

1354
01:56:10,465 --> 01:56:12,258
A cursed life.

1355
01:56:12,467 --> 01:56:14,260
Who would choose such a life?

1356
01:56:14,343 --> 01:56:16,554
COLUMBUS:
I think the centaur works beautifully here,

1357
01:56:16,637 --> 01:56:20,016
because he's mysterious,
he feels as if he's a real animal.

1358
01:56:20,099 --> 01:56:22,977
It's not just a human
attached to a horse body.

1359
01:56:23,060 --> 01:56:27,482
He feels like he's part of this beast
and he's towering and threatening.

1360
01:56:27,565 --> 01:56:30,067
The unicorn back there was actually built

1361
01:56:30,151 --> 01:56:33,279
{\an8}by the person who did most of our prosthetics
in the movie, Nick Dudman.

1362
01:56:33,362 --> 01:56:34,405
{\an8}A genius, Nick.

1363
01:56:34,489 --> 01:56:40,286
{\an8}And Nick built a full-sized unicorn body
and brought it onto the set.

1364
01:56:40,369 --> 01:56:43,372
{\an8}It was actually very sad
to see that unicorn lying there.

1365
01:56:43,456 --> 01:56:46,083
{\an8}But again, our centaur here was voiced

1366
01:56:46,167 --> 01:56:49,295
{\an8}by a very talented actor
from the Royal Shakespeare Company,

1367
01:56:49,378 --> 01:56:52,590
{\an8}then he was completely animated
by a digital company in Los Angeles.

1368
01:56:53,299 --> 01:56:54,300
Good luck.

1369
01:57:02,225 --> 01:57:06,395
{\an8}HERMIONE: You mean, You-Know-Who
is out there right now in the Forest?

1370
01:57:06,479 --> 01:57:09,440
{\an8}But he's weak.
He's living off the unicorns.

1371
01:57:09,524 --> 01:57:12,527
{\an8}Don't you see? We had it wrong.

1372
01:57:12,610 --> 01:57:17,240
{\an8}Snape doesn't want the Stone
for himself. He wants it for Voldemort.

1373
01:57:17,323 --> 01:57:20,368
With the Elixir of Life,
Voldemort will be strong again.

1374
01:57:20,451 --> 01:57:23,663
He'll come back.

1375
01:57:23,746 --> 01:57:25,748
RON:
But if he comes back...

1376
01:57:25,831 --> 01:57:29,877
...you don't think he'll try
to kill you, do you?

1377
01:57:30,753 --> 01:57:34,257
If he'd had the chance,
he might have tried tonight.

1378
01:57:34,507 --> 01:57:38,177
And to think I've been worrying
about my Potions final.

1379
01:57:38,261 --> 01:57:41,889
HERMIONE: Hang on a minute.
We're forgetting one thing.

1380
01:57:42,265 --> 01:57:46,352
Who's the one wizard
Voldemort always feared?

1381
01:57:47,895 --> 01:57:53,150
Dumbledore. As long as Dumbledore
is around, Harry, you're safe.

1382
01:57:53,234 --> 01:57:57,405
As long as Dumbledore is around,
you can't be touched.

1383
01:58:03,244 --> 01:58:08,666
HERMIONE: I'd heard Hogwarts' final
exams were frightful, but that was fun.

1384
01:58:08,749 --> 01:58:12,461
Speak for yourself.
All right there, Harry?

1385
01:58:12,587 --> 01:58:17,758
- My scar. It keeps burning.
- It's happened before.

1386
01:58:18,301 --> 01:58:20,761
- Not like this.
RON: You should see the nurse.

1387
01:58:20,845 --> 01:58:24,390
HARRY: I think it's a warning.
It means danger's coming.

1388
01:58:29,353 --> 01:58:31,314
[FLUTE PLAYS]

1389
01:58:31,981 --> 01:58:34,525
- Of course!
- What is it?

1390
01:58:34,609 --> 01:58:38,529
Isn't it odd that what Hagrid wants
more than anything is a dragon...

1391
01:58:38,613 --> 01:58:41,782
...and a stranger just happens
to have one?

1392
01:58:41,866 --> 01:58:44,660
How many people wander around
with dragon eggs?

1393
01:58:44,744 --> 01:58:47,163
Why didn't I see it before?

1394
01:58:52,627 --> 01:58:56,422
Who gave you the egg?
What did he look like?

1395
01:58:56,505 --> 01:58:59,258
I never saw his face.
He kept his hood up.

1396
01:58:59,342 --> 01:59:01,927
You and this stranger
must have talked.

1397
01:59:02,470 --> 01:59:06,140
He wanted to know what sort
of creatures I looked after.

1398
01:59:06,223 --> 01:59:10,686
I said, "After Fluffy,
a dragon's gonna be no problem."

1399
01:59:10,770 --> 01:59:14,982
- Was he interested in Fluffy?
- Of course he was interested.

1400
01:59:15,316 --> 01:59:19,487
How often do you come across
a three-headed dog?

1401
01:59:19,862 --> 01:59:25,451
But I told him, "The trick with any beast
is to know how to calm him."

1402
01:59:25,534 --> 01:59:29,914
Take Fluffy, for example. Play him
music and he falls straight to sleep.

1403
01:59:32,583 --> 01:59:34,043
I shouldn't have told you that.

1404
01:59:35,586 --> 01:59:37,880
Where are you going?

1405
01:59:44,804 --> 01:59:47,598
We have to see Dumbledore.
Immediately!

1406
01:59:48,015 --> 01:59:50,768
I'm afraid he's not here.

1407
01:59:50,851 --> 01:59:55,189
He received an urgent owl
from the Ministry of Magic and left.

1408
01:59:55,940 --> 02:00:00,653
He's gone? But this is important!
This is about the Philosopher's Stone!

1409
02:00:02,446 --> 02:00:04,949
- How do you know--?
- Someone's going to try and steal it.

1410
02:00:06,826 --> 02:00:11,247
I don't know how you know,
but I assure you it is well protected.

1411
02:00:12,164 --> 02:00:15,626
Now would you go back
to your dormitories? Quietly.

1412
02:00:24,844 --> 02:00:27,763
That was no stranger Hagrid met.
It was Snape.

1413
02:00:27,847 --> 02:00:30,558
Which means he knows
how to get past Fluffy.

1414
02:00:30,641 --> 02:00:33,394
- And with Dumbledore gone--
- Good afternoon.

1415
02:00:36,647 --> 02:00:39,859
What would three young Gryffindors...

1416
02:00:39,942 --> 02:00:44,280
...be doing inside on a day like this?

1417
02:00:49,076 --> 02:00:51,954
- We were just--
- You ought to be careful.

1418
02:00:53,122 --> 02:00:55,166
People will think you're...

1419
02:00:59,378 --> 02:01:01,172
...up to something.

1420
02:01:12,391 --> 02:01:14,393
Now what do we do?

1421
02:01:14,602 --> 02:01:18,355
We go down the trap door. Tonight.

1422
02:01:30,701 --> 02:01:31,952
[TOAD CROAKS]

1423
02:01:32,119 --> 02:01:33,537
HARRY:
Trevor.

1424
02:01:33,913 --> 02:01:36,749
Trevor, go! You shouldn't be here!

1425
02:01:37,875 --> 02:01:43,130
Neither should you.
You're sneaking out again, aren't you?

1426
02:01:43,214 --> 02:01:47,259
- Neville, listen. We were--
- No, I won't let you!

1427
02:01:47,343 --> 02:01:52,014
You'll get Gryffindor into trouble again.
I'll fight you.

1428
02:01:52,223 --> 02:01:56,519
Neville, I'm really sorry about this.
<i>Petrificus Totalus.</i>

1429
02:02:04,485 --> 02:02:08,239
{\an8}You're a little scary sometimes,
you know that?

1430
02:02:08,531 --> 02:02:12,159
{\an8}Brilliant, but scary.

1431
02:02:13,077 --> 02:02:14,662
{\an8}Let's go.

1432
02:02:15,079 --> 02:02:18,916
HERMIONE: Sorry.
RON: It's for your own good, you know.

1433
02:02:24,755 --> 02:02:28,092
- You stood on my foot!
- Sorry.

1434
02:02:32,596 --> 02:02:34,598
HERMIONE:
<i>Alohomora.</i>

1435
02:02:46,610 --> 02:02:49,238
{\an8}HARRY:
Wait a minute. He's...

1436
02:02:50,447 --> 02:02:52,199
{\an8}...snoring.

1437
02:02:55,119 --> 02:03:00,666
HARRY: Snape's already been here.
He's put a spell on the harp.

1438
02:03:02,251 --> 02:03:04,169
RON:
It's got horrible breath.

1439
02:03:05,045 --> 02:03:09,091
{\an8}Here we have
our three-headed dog sequence.

1440
02:03:09,174 --> 02:03:13,554
This was a scene where we had to create
a CGI three-headed animal,

1441
02:03:13,637 --> 02:03:15,723
and I thought they did a wonderful job.

1442
02:03:15,806 --> 02:03:19,560
When they moved the paw, we created
a giant, furry paw for the kids to move.

1443
02:03:19,643 --> 02:03:23,355
But when they lifted it, practically,
the paw just looked like a giant stuffed animal.

1444
02:03:23,439 --> 02:03:26,650
So we had to literally draw over it
using our computer animation,

1445
02:03:26,734 --> 02:03:29,653
so when the kids lifted the paw
off of the trap door,

1446
02:03:29,737 --> 02:03:31,947
there was actually some movement
in the fingers,

1447
02:03:32,031 --> 02:03:35,034
and it felt like it was real
and it was alive.

1448
02:03:40,831 --> 02:03:44,460
I'll go first. Don't follow
until I give you a sign.

1449
02:03:44,543 --> 02:03:48,839
If something bad happens,
get yourselves out.

1450
02:03:50,466 --> 02:03:53,969
Does it seem a bit quiet to you?

1451
02:03:54,637 --> 02:03:56,013
The harp.

1452
02:03:57,139 --> 02:03:58,974
It's stopped playing.

1453
02:04:01,268 --> 02:04:04,313
Ugh. Yuck!

1454
02:04:09,860 --> 02:04:11,028
HARRY:
Jump!

1455
02:04:16,784 --> 02:04:19,662
[RON SCREAMS]

1456
02:04:23,374 --> 02:04:24,458
Whoa.

1457
02:04:25,209 --> 02:04:27,920
{\an8}Lucky this plant thing's here, really.

1458
02:04:28,712 --> 02:04:30,506
{\an8}Whoa!

1459
02:04:43,227 --> 02:04:46,480
{\an8}HERMIONE: Stop moving, both of you.
This is Devil's Snare.

1460
02:04:46,605 --> 02:04:50,401
{\an8}You have to relax. If you don't,
it will only kill you faster.

1461
02:04:50,484 --> 02:04:54,822
{\an8}Kill us faster?
Oh, now I can relax!

1462
02:04:55,990 --> 02:04:57,616
COLUMBUS:
So for Devil's Snare,

1463
02:04:57,700 --> 02:04:59,910
{\an8}I said, "Okay, let's us build Devil's Snare,

1464
02:04:59,994 --> 02:05:04,331
{\an8}and I'll shoot it in a way that we don't
have to incorporate any digital effects.

1465
02:05:04,415 --> 02:05:06,333
I'll shoot it in reverse."

1466
02:05:06,417 --> 02:05:11,505
So all of these sequences are actually done
with real, practical puppeteers,

1467
02:05:11,588 --> 02:05:13,465
below the Devil's Snare set,

1468
02:05:13,549 --> 02:05:17,136
actually moving the tentacles
in each sequence.

1469
02:05:17,219 --> 02:05:19,346
And when the kids are wrapped
with the tentacles,

1470
02:05:19,430 --> 02:05:22,099
the kids were actually able
to act in reverse.

1471
02:05:22,182 --> 02:05:25,686
It's better than any CGI version of it
we could have ever done.

1472
02:05:25,769 --> 02:05:28,397
Because the kids, who needed it at the time,

1473
02:05:28,480 --> 02:05:30,858
as opposed to dealing with
just a green screen situation,

1474
02:05:30,941 --> 02:05:34,695
were actually able to act
with real, tangible effects

1475
02:05:34,778 --> 02:05:37,114
and it worked beautifully.

1476
02:05:37,197 --> 02:05:39,283
<i>Lumus Solem.</i>

1477
02:05:45,664 --> 02:05:47,875
{\an8}And Hermione saves the day,
which is a huge moment.

1478
02:05:47,958 --> 02:05:52,755
{\an8}Only visual effects shot is the shot of the wand
coming up through the Devil's Snare sequence,

1479
02:05:52,838 --> 02:05:54,673
{\an8}through the Devil's Snare area.

1480
02:05:54,757 --> 02:05:57,176
{\an8}And I love the fact that Hermione
has her moment there.

1481
02:05:57,259 --> 02:05:59,887
{\an8}It's just a great, wonderful moment for her.

1482
02:05:59,970 --> 02:06:00,971
[WINGS FLUTTERING]

1483
02:06:01,055 --> 02:06:02,639
HERMIONE:
What is that?

1484
02:06:02,723 --> 02:06:06,435
I don't know. Sounds like wings.

1485
02:06:19,615 --> 02:06:23,202
HERMIONE: Curious.
I've never seen birds like these.

1486
02:06:23,285 --> 02:06:26,914
HARRY: They're not birds.
They're keys.

1487
02:06:27,122 --> 02:06:29,792
And I'll bet one of them
fits that door.

1488
02:06:34,004 --> 02:06:37,925
- What's this all about?
- I don't know.

1489
02:06:44,515 --> 02:06:45,974
Strange.

1490
02:06:47,017 --> 02:06:48,811
RON:
<i>Alohomora!</i>

1491
02:06:52,272 --> 02:06:54,525
Well, it was worth a try.

1492
02:06:54,608 --> 02:06:58,112
What will we do?
There must be a thousand keys.

1493
02:06:58,195 --> 02:07:02,241
RON: We want a big, old-fashioned one.
Probably rusty.

1494
02:07:02,324 --> 02:07:05,744
I see it!
The one with the broken wing.

1495
02:07:09,331 --> 02:07:11,041
What's wrong?

1496
02:07:12,543 --> 02:07:14,044
It's too simple.

1497
02:07:14,253 --> 02:07:19,007
Go on! If Snape could catch it
on that old broomstick, you can.

1498
02:07:19,216 --> 02:07:21,760
You're the youngest Seeker
in a century.

1499
02:07:39,611 --> 02:07:41,446
{\an8}This complicates things a bit.

1500
02:08:03,886 --> 02:08:05,804
HARRY:
Catch the key!

1501
02:08:10,225 --> 02:08:11,643
Hurry up!

1502
02:08:44,635 --> 02:08:49,389
HERMIONE: I don't like this.
I don't like this at all.

1503
02:08:49,473 --> 02:08:52,643
Where are we? A graveyard.

1504
02:08:53,060 --> 02:08:55,103
This is no graveyard.

1505
02:09:03,153 --> 02:09:04,863
It's a chessboard.

1506
02:09:04,947 --> 02:09:08,867
{\an8}Here we have Wizard's Chess, one of
the 50 sequences I was most excited about doing.

1507
02:09:08,951 --> 02:09:10,911
{\an8}The great thing about these Harry Potter books

1508
02:09:10,994 --> 02:09:15,165
{\an8}is that every sequence, as a director,
you're like a kid in a candy store.

1509
02:09:15,249 --> 02:09:17,709
{\an8}But for me, this was an exciting sequence,

1510
02:09:17,793 --> 02:09:19,503
{\an8}because we could have, again,

1511
02:09:19,586 --> 02:09:22,965
{\an8}built all of this in a digital environment,
put the kids in a green-screen world,

1512
02:09:23,048 --> 02:09:24,049
{\an8}but we didn't.

1513
02:09:24,132 --> 02:09:26,760
{\an8}Stuart Craig built this entire set

1514
02:09:26,843 --> 02:09:29,972
{\an8}and created each one of those chess pieces.

1515
02:09:30,055 --> 02:09:32,307
{\an8}So, when you walked onto that set,

1516
02:09:32,391 --> 02:09:35,686
{\an8}you saw all of these life-size chess pieces

1517
02:09:35,769 --> 02:09:38,188
{\an8}and this chessboard surrounded by fire,

1518
02:09:38,272 --> 02:09:40,357
{\an8}and it was amazing.

1519
02:09:40,440 --> 02:09:43,360
{\an8}I mean, I was in awe
of what Stuart had done here.

1520
02:09:43,443 --> 02:09:46,405
{\an8}I wanted to take several of the pieces
back to America with me

1521
02:09:46,488 --> 02:09:48,699
{\an8}and put them up around my house,
I was so impressed.

1522
02:09:48,782 --> 02:09:50,617
{\an8}They looked like these wonderful sculptures.

1523
02:09:50,701 --> 02:09:53,328
{\an8}And we utilized CGI in certain elements.

1524
02:09:53,412 --> 02:09:57,124
{\an8}When you see the pawns draw their swords,
those sort of things,

1525
02:09:57,207 --> 02:10:01,211
{\an8}we utilized CGI to create a sense
of movement among the chess pieces.

1526
02:10:01,295 --> 02:10:03,797
{\an8}But all of these other chess pieces are real.

1527
02:10:03,880 --> 02:10:05,549
{\an8}And they even moved forward.

1528
02:10:05,632 --> 02:10:09,845
{\an8}When Ron's chess piece moves forward here,
when he's making his tremendous sacrifice,

1529
02:10:09,928 --> 02:10:11,138
these were practical.

1530
02:10:11,221 --> 02:10:13,473
And the combined movement of the camera,

1531
02:10:13,557 --> 02:10:17,019
along with the pieces mechanically moving
along the floor,

1532
02:10:17,102 --> 02:10:20,981
created a real sense of terror
and a real suspenseful moment.

1533
02:10:21,064 --> 02:10:23,400
{\an8}There was talk about
making them move more quickly,

1534
02:10:23,483 --> 02:10:27,029
{\an8}and I just loved the fact
that this sequence happened

1535
02:10:27,112 --> 02:10:28,405
{\an8}at its own pace.

1536
02:10:28,488 --> 02:10:30,824
{\an8}One of my favorite shots in the movie

1537
02:10:30,907 --> 02:10:34,578
{\an8}is Ron really deciding to sacrifice himself.

1538
02:10:34,661 --> 02:10:38,707
{\an8}And that to me is just
an amazing performance by a kid

1539
02:10:38,790 --> 02:10:41,293
{\an8}who was starting to feel
very comfortable with his character.

1540
02:10:41,376 --> 02:10:43,712
{\an8}He sees the power of these things,

1541
02:10:43,795 --> 02:10:47,007
{\an8}and he realizes he's gotta sacrifice himself
for his friends.

1542
02:10:47,090 --> 02:10:52,387
{\an8}I sensed a real moment of fear
but also courage from Rupert at that point.

1543
02:10:52,471 --> 02:10:55,223
{\an8}Probably his best performance in the film.

1544
02:10:59,186 --> 02:11:01,646
Castle to e4!

1545
02:11:05,275 --> 02:11:07,611
Pawn to c3!

1546
02:11:52,239 --> 02:11:56,368
- Wait a minute.
RON: You understand right, Harry.

1547
02:11:56,451 --> 02:12:00,831
Once I make my move,
the queen will take me.

1548
02:12:01,832 --> 02:12:04,292
Then you're free to check the king.

1549
02:12:04,376 --> 02:12:07,087
- No. Ron, no!
- What is it?

1550
02:12:07,671 --> 02:12:12,509
- He's going to sacrifice himself.
- No, there must be another way!

1551
02:12:12,592 --> 02:12:16,471
Do you wanna stop Snape
from getting that Stone or not?

1552
02:12:16,555 --> 02:12:20,225
Harry, it's you that has to go on.
I know it.

1553
02:12:20,642 --> 02:12:23,353
Not me. Not Hermione. You.

1554
02:12:33,655 --> 02:12:36,575
{\an8}Knight to h3.

1555
02:12:57,512 --> 02:12:59,097
Check.

1556
02:13:22,579 --> 02:13:24,289
[RON SCREAMS]

1557
02:13:28,668 --> 02:13:30,253
Ron!

1558
02:13:30,754 --> 02:13:35,884
No, don't move!
Don't forget, we're still playing.

1559
02:13:51,525 --> 02:13:52,776
Checkmate.

1560
02:14:12,754 --> 02:14:15,382
Take care of Ron.
Then go to the owlery.

1561
02:14:15,465 --> 02:14:19,386
Send a message to Dumbledore.
Ron's right.

1562
02:14:19,469 --> 02:14:21,471
I have to go on.

1563
02:14:21,930 --> 02:14:27,394
You'll be okay, Harry.
You're a great wizard. You really are.

1564
02:14:28,103 --> 02:14:29,896
Not as good as you.

1565
02:14:31,398 --> 02:14:36,278
Me? Books and cleverness.
There are more important things.

1566
02:14:37,445 --> 02:14:43,159
Friendship and bravery.
And, Harry, just be careful.

1567
02:15:21,156 --> 02:15:22,824
{\an8}You?

1568
02:15:23,617 --> 02:15:27,537
{\an8}No, it can't be.
Snape, he was the--

1569
02:15:27,621 --> 02:15:30,832
{\an8}QUIRRELL: Yes, he does seem the type,
doesn't he?

1570
02:15:30,915 --> 02:15:34,044
{\an8}Next to him, who would suspect...

1571
02:15:34,127 --> 02:15:37,297
{\an8}...poor, stuttering
Professor Quirrell?

1572
02:15:38,006 --> 02:15:44,012
{\an8}But that day, during the Quidditch match,
Snape tried to kill me.

1573
02:15:44,095 --> 02:15:46,765
{\an8}No, dear boy. I tried to kill you!

1574
02:15:47,265 --> 02:15:51,561
{\an8}If Snape's cloak hadn't caught
fire and broken my eye contact...

1575
02:15:51,645 --> 02:15:53,855
{\an8}...I would have succeeded.

1576
02:15:54,064 --> 02:15:57,067
{\an8}Even with Snape muttering
his countercurse.

1577
02:15:57,275 --> 02:15:59,486
{\an8}Snape was trying to save me?

1578
02:15:59,569 --> 02:16:04,032
{\an8}I knew you were a danger to me,
especially after Halloween.

1579
02:16:05,241 --> 02:16:09,621
- Then you let the troll in!
- Very good, Potter, yes.

1580
02:16:09,704 --> 02:16:12,791
Snape, unfortunately, wasn't fooled.

1581
02:16:13,375 --> 02:16:17,212
While everyone ran about, he went
to the third floor to head me off.

1582
02:16:19,214 --> 02:16:22,676
He, of course, never trusted me again.

1583
02:16:23,677 --> 02:16:28,264
He rarely left me alone.
But he doesn't understand.

1584
02:16:29,099 --> 02:16:32,560
I'm never alone. Never.

1585
02:16:33,395 --> 02:16:36,940
Now, what does this mirror do?

1586
02:16:39,067 --> 02:16:41,236
I see what I desire.

1587
02:16:41,736 --> 02:16:46,282
I see myself holding the Stone.
But how do I get it?

1588
02:16:46,366 --> 02:16:48,535
MAN:
Use the boy.

1589
02:16:49,327 --> 02:16:52,872
Come here, Potter! Now!

1590
02:17:05,343 --> 02:17:08,680
Tell me, what do you see?

1591
02:17:34,497 --> 02:17:36,374
What is it? What do you see?

1592
02:17:37,125 --> 02:17:42,422
I'm shaking hands with Dumbledore.
I've won the house cup.

1593
02:17:42,505 --> 02:17:44,132
MAN:
He lies.

1594
02:17:44,716 --> 02:17:48,344
Tell the truth! What do you see?

1595
02:17:48,428 --> 02:17:52,849
MAN: Let me speak to him.
- Master, you are not strong enough.

1596
02:17:52,932 --> 02:17:57,103
MAN:
I have strength enough for this.

1597
02:17:59,564 --> 02:18:00,899
{\an8}Very interesting scene here.

1598
02:18:00,982 --> 02:18:04,027
{\an8}This is our first reveal of Voldemort
in any of the films.

1599
02:18:04,110 --> 02:18:07,989
{\an8}This was prior to the casting of Ralph Fiennes

1600
02:18:08,072 --> 02:18:11,367
{\an8}so ironically, in a weird way,

1601
02:18:11,451 --> 02:18:15,830
this Voldemort kind of resembles
the Ralph Fiennes you see in the later pictures.

1602
02:18:15,914 --> 02:18:18,416
I always thought I would want to go back--

1603
02:18:18,500 --> 02:18:20,585
again, as a director,
you always want to go back--

1604
02:18:20,668 --> 02:18:24,756
want to go back and reshoot this,
or reshoot that particular part of it,

1605
02:18:24,839 --> 02:18:27,342
{\an8}so the films would have a real consistency.

1606
02:18:27,425 --> 02:18:32,180
{\an8}It would be great to reshoot it
with Ralph Fiennes' voice and look now.

1607
02:18:32,263 --> 02:18:33,681
{\an8}This is pretty close.

1608
02:18:33,765 --> 02:18:38,061
{\an8}But it's not exactly where we are
in the later pictures.

1609
02:18:38,144 --> 02:18:41,731
But for a visual effect at the time,
I was very impressed

1610
02:18:41,815 --> 02:18:44,317
at what our visual effects department
came up with here.

1611
02:18:44,400 --> 02:18:46,653
Because it was a concept
that was quite odd.

1612
02:18:47,487 --> 02:18:50,365
{\an8}Only Jo Rowling could have come up with the fact

1613
02:18:50,448 --> 02:18:53,660
{\an8}that Voldemort appears
out of the back of a man's head.

1614
02:18:53,743 --> 02:18:58,540
{\an8}It's kind of a grotesque and fascinating idea.
How do you do it?

1615
02:18:58,623 --> 02:19:04,295
{\an8}Well, we had our actor wearing
little green dots on the back of his head,

1616
02:19:04,379 --> 02:19:07,590
{\an8}and then Voldemort was added much later.

1617
02:19:07,674 --> 02:19:12,262
{\an8}I was just intrigued by this sequence,
because I thought it would be so horrifying.

1618
02:19:12,345 --> 02:19:15,515
And we wanted to make it fairly horrifying
for the little kiddies out there.

1619
02:19:15,598 --> 02:19:19,269
I thought it would be so horrifying
that the film would get a PG-13,

1620
02:19:19,352 --> 02:19:21,563
which is not what we wanted
on the first Potter film.

1621
02:19:21,896 --> 02:19:24,858
But for some reason,
kids weren't running out of the theater.

1622
02:19:24,941 --> 02:19:27,402
They were emotionally invested
in the film at this point.

1623
02:19:27,485 --> 02:19:29,654
Because I think there was
an emotional quality here.

1624
02:19:29,737 --> 02:19:31,531
{\an8}When you combine Harry's parents

1625
02:19:31,614 --> 02:19:35,326
{\an8}along with this hideous Voldemort face,

1626
02:19:35,410 --> 02:19:40,665
{\an8}I think that you sort of temper it a little bit,
you soften it a little for the kids in the audience.

1627
02:19:41,666 --> 02:19:43,751
{\an8}The casting of Harry's parents was difficult

1628
02:19:43,835 --> 02:19:46,546
because we knew they would be
in subsequent pictures,

1629
02:19:46,629 --> 02:19:48,631
but at this point, we hadn't read all the books,

1630
02:19:48,715 --> 02:19:51,551
{\an8}so we didn't know if they would appear
in book five, six, seven.

1631
02:19:51,634 --> 02:19:53,011
{\an8}We had no idea.

1632
02:19:53,094 --> 02:19:55,930
{\an8}And Jo really didn't give us
that particular information.

1633
02:19:56,014 --> 02:20:00,184
{\an8}So we cast people who have since
appeared in subsequent pictures,

1634
02:20:00,268 --> 02:20:03,813
{\an8}and we didn't know if they would get to speak
or how much we would get to know them.

1635
02:20:03,897 --> 02:20:07,942
{\an8}This was done with-- again, we built this set.

1636
02:20:08,902 --> 02:20:11,613
{\an8}That's all real fire in the background,

1637
02:20:11,696 --> 02:20:17,327
{\an8}again, in an effort to give the kids a sense
of tangible things they could hold onto.

1638
02:20:36,054 --> 02:20:40,808
{\an8}- What is this magic?
- Fool, get the Stone!

1639
02:20:42,685 --> 02:20:44,854
{\an8}Our actor here who played Quirrell,

1640
02:20:44,938 --> 02:20:47,357
{\an8}was there for Dan all the time.

1641
02:20:47,440 --> 02:20:52,320
Obviously, when his face is burning
and disintegrating, these are all CGI effects.

1642
02:20:53,404 --> 02:20:56,532
To do this practically
would probably hurt someone.

1643
02:20:56,616 --> 02:20:58,201
We didn't do that.

1644
02:20:58,284 --> 02:21:01,829
This was a little homage
to one of my favorite pictures from the late '50s,

1645
02:21:01,913 --> 02:21:06,709
<i>Horror of Dracula,</i> one of the Hammer films,
where Christopher Lee disintegrates at the end.

1646
02:21:07,210 --> 02:21:10,338
{\an8}I think I even borrowed a shot
from that final sequence,

1647
02:21:10,421 --> 02:21:12,799
{\an8}where Christopher Lee is defeated
by Peter Cushing.

1648
02:21:12,882 --> 02:21:18,346
{\an8}And our stone, the big moment in our movie,

1649
02:21:18,429 --> 02:21:21,849
the Sorcerer's Stone, the Philosopher's Stone,
was really created out of plastic.

1650
02:21:21,933 --> 02:21:25,561
We had several of these
that were made by our prop department.

1651
02:21:25,645 --> 02:21:28,731
Sometimes they looked like candy.
They weren't shiny enough.

1652
02:21:28,815 --> 02:21:31,442
And the only way we could ever get
the sense of a reflection

1653
02:21:31,526 --> 02:21:33,778
was to put a reflection
of a flame in there.

1654
02:21:33,861 --> 02:21:37,240
Voldemort here is obviously created
through a CGI effect,

1655
02:21:37,323 --> 02:21:39,951
which was very effective.

1656
02:21:40,034 --> 02:21:44,539
Again, in Jo's world, which is so wonderful
and imaginative and amazing,

1657
02:21:44,622 --> 02:21:46,708
Voldemort actually has to pass through Harry,

1658
02:21:46,791 --> 02:21:49,711
which I just thought was something
I'd never seen before.

1659
02:22:26,664 --> 02:22:28,583
Good afternoon, Harry.

1660
02:22:31,294 --> 02:22:35,882
- Tokens from your admirers?
- Admirers?

1661
02:22:35,965 --> 02:22:42,096
What happened in the dungeons between
you and Professor Quirrell is a secret.

1662
02:22:42,180 --> 02:22:46,517
So, naturally, the whole school knows.

1663
02:22:49,312 --> 02:22:53,107
I see that your friend Ronald
has saved you the trouble...

1664
02:22:53,191 --> 02:22:56,152
...of opening your Chocolate Frogs.

1665
02:22:56,235 --> 02:22:59,155
Ron was here? Is he all right?
What about Hermione?

1666
02:22:59,614 --> 02:23:03,659
Fine. They're both just fine.

1667
02:23:04,911 --> 02:23:07,830
- What happened to the Stone?
- Relax, dear boy.

1668
02:23:07,914 --> 02:23:10,208
The Stone has been destroyed.

1669
02:23:11,542 --> 02:23:14,170
My friend Nicolas and I
have had a little chat...

1670
02:23:14,253 --> 02:23:18,883
...and agreed it was best all around.

1671
02:23:19,926 --> 02:23:22,970
But then, Flamel,
he'll die, won't he?

1672
02:23:25,598 --> 02:23:30,144
He has enough Elixir
to set his affairs in order.

1673
02:23:31,312 --> 02:23:34,649
But yes, he will die.

1674
02:23:34,732 --> 02:23:37,276
How is it I got the Stone, sir?

1675
02:23:37,360 --> 02:23:40,071
One minute I was staring
in the mirror and--

1676
02:23:40,154 --> 02:23:43,616
You see, only a person...

1677
02:23:44,617 --> 02:23:48,454
...who wanted to find the Stone,
find it...

1678
02:23:48,538 --> 02:23:52,625
...but not use it,
would be able to get it.

1679
02:23:54,210 --> 02:23:57,797
That is one of my more brilliant ideas.

1680
02:23:57,880 --> 02:24:02,301
And between you and me,
that is saying something.

1681
02:24:04,387 --> 02:24:09,767
Does that mean, with the Stone gone,
that Voldemort can never come back?

1682
02:24:09,851 --> 02:24:11,894
I'm afraid...

1683
02:24:13,563 --> 02:24:16,649
...there are ways
in which he can return.

1684
02:24:18,359 --> 02:24:21,028
Harry, do you know why...

1685
02:24:21,112 --> 02:24:24,657
...Professor Quirrell couldn't bear
to have you touch him?

1686
02:24:25,366 --> 02:24:30,079
It was because of your mother.
She sacrificed herself for you.

1687
02:24:30,663 --> 02:24:33,082
And that kind of act leaves a mark.

1688
02:24:33,916 --> 02:24:37,837
No, this kind of mark cannot be seen.

1689
02:24:37,920 --> 02:24:42,967
- It lives in your very skin.
- What is it?

1690
02:24:43,718 --> 02:24:47,430
{\an8}Love, Harry. Love.

1691
02:24:55,521 --> 02:24:59,609
Bertie Bott's Every Flavor Beans.

1692
02:24:59,692 --> 02:25:04,530
I was most unfortunate in my youth
to come across a vomit-flavored one.

1693
02:25:04,614 --> 02:25:08,201
{\an8}And since then,
I've lost my liking for them.

1694
02:25:08,284 --> 02:25:11,787
{\an8}But I think I could be safe...

1695
02:25:11,871 --> 02:25:13,915
{\an8}...with a nice toffee.

1696
02:25:16,959 --> 02:25:19,879
{\an8}Hm, alas!

1697
02:25:20,588 --> 02:25:22,215
{\an8}Earwax.

1698
02:25:37,939 --> 02:25:41,192
- All right there, Ron?
- All right. You?

1699
02:25:42,235 --> 02:25:45,029
All right. Hermione?

1700
02:25:45,613 --> 02:25:47,448
Never better.

1701
02:26:03,256 --> 02:26:05,800
Another year gone.

1702
02:26:06,550 --> 02:26:11,138
And now, as I understand it,
the house cup needs awarding.

1703
02:26:11,222 --> 02:26:13,975
And the points stand thus:

1704
02:26:14,058 --> 02:26:18,604
In fourth place,
Gryffindor with 312 points.

1705
02:26:21,857 --> 02:26:27,530
Third place,
Hufflepuff with 352 points.

1706
02:26:32,702 --> 02:26:34,829
In second place...

1707
02:26:34,912 --> 02:26:39,625
...Ravenclaw with 426 points.

1708
02:26:45,214 --> 02:26:47,049
And in first place...

1709
02:26:47,133 --> 02:26:52,263
...with 472 points, Slytherin house.

1710
02:26:58,311 --> 02:27:00,604
Nice one, mate.

1711
02:27:04,400 --> 02:27:07,528
{\an8}Yes, well done, Slytherin.
Well done.

1712
02:27:07,611 --> 02:27:13,117
{\an8}However, recent events must
be taken into account.

1713
02:27:13,200 --> 02:27:17,455
{\an8}And I have a few last-minute points
to award.

1714
02:27:18,831 --> 02:27:24,086
To Miss Hermione Granger,
for the cool use of intellect...

1715
02:27:24,503 --> 02:27:27,381
...while others were in grave peril...

1716
02:27:28,090 --> 02:27:29,884
...50 points.

1717
02:27:31,218 --> 02:27:32,553
Good job.

1718
02:27:40,186 --> 02:27:46,317
Second, to Mr. Ronald Weasley,
for the best-played game of chess...

1719
02:27:46,817 --> 02:27:52,073
...that Hogwarts has seen
these many years, 50 points.

1720
02:27:56,577 --> 02:27:58,162
{\an8}And third...

1721
02:27:59,288 --> 02:28:02,208
{\an8}...to Mr. Harry Potter...

1722
02:28:02,291 --> 02:28:06,670
{\an8}...for pure nerve
and outstanding courage...

1723
02:28:07,213 --> 02:28:12,134
{\an8}...I award Gryffindor house 60 points.

1724
02:28:20,393 --> 02:28:21,769
{\an8}We're tied with Slytherin!

1725
02:28:22,561 --> 02:28:28,567
{\an8}Finally, it takes a great deal of bravery
to stand up to your enemies...

1726
02:28:28,651 --> 02:28:32,113
{\an8}...but a great deal more
to stand up to your friends.

1727
02:28:32,780 --> 02:28:35,866
{\an8}I award 10 points...

1728
02:28:35,950 --> 02:28:38,536
{\an8}...to Neville Longbottom.

1729
02:28:52,466 --> 02:28:55,052
{\an8}Assuming that my calculations
are correct...

1730
02:28:55,136 --> 02:28:59,932
{\an8}...I believe that a change
of decoration is in order.

1731
02:29:05,646 --> 02:29:09,108
Gryffindor wins the house cup.

1732
02:29:11,193 --> 02:29:12,653
Yes!

1733
02:29:28,794 --> 02:29:30,045
We won!

1734
02:29:44,226 --> 02:29:46,729
[TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS]

1735
02:29:47,313 --> 02:29:50,024
HAGRID: Come on, now.
Hurry up, you'll be late.

1736
02:29:50,691 --> 02:29:54,278
Train's leaving. Go on.
Come on, hurry up.

1737
02:30:00,409 --> 02:30:03,204
- Come on, Harry.
- One minute.

1738
02:30:10,002 --> 02:30:13,130
Thought you were leaving
without saying goodbye, did you?

1739
02:30:16,926 --> 02:30:18,761
This is for you.

1740
02:30:35,528 --> 02:30:36,612
Thanks, Hagrid.

1741
02:30:43,452 --> 02:30:48,040
{\an8}Go on. On with you. On with you now.
Oh, listen, Harry.

1742
02:30:48,123 --> 02:30:52,878
{\an8}If that dolt of a cousin of yours,
Dudley, gives you any grief...

1743
02:30:52,962 --> 02:30:55,798
{\an8}...you could always threaten him...

1744
02:30:55,881 --> 02:30:58,884
...with a nice pair of ears
to go with his tail.

1745
02:30:58,968 --> 02:31:04,223
But we're not allowed to do magic
away from Hogwarts. You know that.

1746
02:31:04,306 --> 02:31:08,936
I do. But your cousin don't, do he?

1747
02:31:10,980 --> 02:31:14,358
COLUMBUS: Dan's first spoken line
in a Harry Potter movie

1748
02:31:14,441 --> 02:31:17,695
{\an8}comes when he says,
"I'm not going home. Not really."

1749
02:31:17,778 --> 02:31:19,863
I'm not going home.

1750
02:31:19,947 --> 02:31:20,990
Not really.

1751
02:31:21,073 --> 02:31:22,866
{\an8}And when he says that,

1752
02:31:22,950 --> 02:31:25,119
{\an8}when I saw the dailies to that,

1753
02:31:25,202 --> 02:31:27,663
{\an8}I was actually very touched.
I had tears in my eyes.

1754
02:31:27,746 --> 02:31:30,124
{\an8}I looked over at David Heyman.
He's got tears in his eyes.

1755
02:31:30,249 --> 02:31:35,671
{\an8}And I said, "How is it this kid came up
with such a very unsentimental, real performance?"

1756
02:31:35,754 --> 02:31:39,133
{\an8}And that is just a testament
to Dan's ability as an actor,

1757
02:31:39,216 --> 02:31:41,176
{\an8}even from the very first day on this film.

1758
02:32:04,950 --> 02:32:07,286
I hope you guys had
a wonderful time watching this.

1759
02:32:07,369 --> 02:32:09,121
I could talk about this forever,

1760
02:32:09,455 --> 02:32:10,372
{\an8}so, thank you so much.

1761
02:32:10,456 --> 02:32:15,836
{\an8}This has been a real pleasure for me
to revisit the world of Harry Potter,

1762
02:32:15,919 --> 02:32:17,463
{\an8}which means so much to me. Thanks.

1763
02:40:12,813 --> 02:40:15,816
NARRATOR:
<i>Well, there were a few close calls,</i>

1764
02:40:15,899 --> 02:40:21,571
<i>mean monsters,
poisonous professors and wicked wizards.</i>

1765
02:40:21,655 --> 02:40:25,242
<i>But Harry, Ron and Hermione
survived their first year at Hogwarts.</i>

1766
02:40:26,243 --> 02:40:28,370
<i>Now how did you fare?</i>

1767
02:40:29,287 --> 02:40:30,664
<i>Time to add up your points.</i>

1768
02:40:30,747 --> 02:40:34,376
<i>To begin, let's see where
the Golden Snitch was buzzing about.</i>

1769
02:40:34,918 --> 02:40:36,586
<i>Didn't waste any time, I see.</i>

1770
02:40:37,045 --> 02:40:39,464
<i>A cozy common room,
can't say I blame you.</i>

1771
02:40:40,257 --> 02:40:42,467
<i>A-ha! Easy-peasy.</i>

1772
02:40:43,009 --> 02:40:45,387
<i>It would take a Seeker
to get you up there.</i>

1773
02:40:46,388 --> 02:40:48,348
<i>Sneaky little Snitch, aren't you?</i>

1774
02:40:49,224 --> 02:40:51,309
<i>Hello, hello, hello.</i>

1775
02:40:51,393 --> 02:40:56,398
<i>Right then, award yourself 25 points
for every Snitch you spotted.</i>

1776
02:40:56,481 --> 02:40:58,650
{\an8}<i>And onto the Hogwarts Trivia Challenge.</i>

1777
02:40:59,234 --> 02:41:02,404
<i>Score five points for every question
